{"title_page": "Darjeeling", "text_new": "{{short description|City in West Bengal, India}}\n{{About|the municipality in West Bengal, India|its namesake district|Darjeeling district|the tea named after the region|Darjeeling tea}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Darjeeling\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang =\n| other_name  =\n| other_name_lang=\n| settlement_type = City\n| image_skyline = Darjeeling.jpg\n| image_alt =\n| image_caption = A view of Darjeeling from the [[Happy Valley Tea Estate]]\n| nickname = The Queen of Hills\n| map_alt  = Darjeeling is located at the norther tip of West Bengal, near its boundary with Sikkim.\n| map_caption =\n| pushpin_map  = India West Bengal#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt =\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in West Bengal, India\n| coordinates = {{coord|27|3|N|88|16|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name  = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1 = State\n| subdivision_name1 = [[West Bengal]]\n| subdivision_type2  = District\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Darjeeling district|Darjeeling]]\n| established_title = Settled\n| established_date  = 1815, [[Treaty of Sugauli]]\n| founder  = [[East India Company]]\n| named_for =\n| government_type = [[Municipal Corporations in India]]\n| governing_body = [[Darjeeling Municipality]]\n| leader_title1= [[Chairman]]\n| leader_name1 = Pratibha Rai<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://siliguritimes.com/pratibha-rai-takes-chairperson-darjeeling-municipal-corporation/ |title=Pratibha Rai Takes Over As Chairperson Of Darjeeling Municipal Corporation |website=Siliguri Times |date=17 January 2018 |accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref>\n| leader_title2 = [[Vice-Chairman]]\n| leader_name2  = Sagar Tamang\n| unit_pref = Metric\n| area_footnotes =\n| area_rank =\n| area_total_km2 = 10.57\n| elevation_footnotes =<ref name=\"DistProf\" />\n| elevation_m = 2042.16\n| population_total = 132016\n| population_as_of = 2011\n| population_rank =\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym =\n| population_note =\n| demographics_type1 = Languages\n| demographics1_title1 = Official\n| demographics1_info1 = [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and [[Nepali language|Nepali]]<ref name=nclm50>{{cite web |url=http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM50thReport.pdf |title=Report of the Commissioner for Linguistic Minorities in India: 50th report (delivered to the Lokh Sabha in 2014) |page=95 |publisher=National Commissioner for Linguistic Minorities, Ministry of Minority Affairs, Government of India |accessdate=13 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708012438/http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM50thReport.pdf |archivedate=8 July 2016  }}</ref>\n| timezone1 = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1 = +5:30\n| postal_code_type = [[Postal Index Number]]\n| postal_code  = 734101\n| area_code_type = Telephone code\n| area_code  = 0354\n| registration_plate = WB-76 WB-77\n| blank1_name_sec1  = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1 = [[Darjeeling (Lok Sabha constituency)|Darjeeling]]\n| blank2_name_sec1 = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1 = [[Darjeeling (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Darjeeling]]\n| website = {{URL|darjeelingmunicipality.org.in}}\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Darjeeling''' ({{IPA-bn|\u02c8dar\u02ccd\u0292ili\u014b|lang}}, {{IPA-ne|dar\u02c8dzi\u02d0li\u014b|lang}}) is a city and a municipality in the [[India]]n [[States and union territories of India|state]] of [[West Bengal]]. It is located in the [[Lesser Himalaya]]s at an elevation of {{convert|6700|ft|order=flip}}. It is noted for its [[tea]] industry, its views of [[Kangchenjunga]], the world's third-highest mountain, and the [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway]], a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]. Darjeeling is the headquarters of the [[Darjeeling district]] which has a partially autonomous status called [[Gorkhaland Territorial Administration]] within the state of West Bengal. It is also a popular tourist destination in India.\n\nThe recorded history of the town starts from the early 19th century when the colonial administration under the [[British Raj]] set up a [[sanatorium]] and a military depot in the region. Subsequently, extensive tea plantations were established in the region and tea growers developed hybrids of [[black tea]] and created new [[fermentation]] techniques. The resultant distinctive [[Darjeeling tea]] is internationally recognised and ranks among the most popular black teas in the world.{{sfn|Srivastava|2003|p=4024}} The Darjeeling Himalayan Railway connects the town with the plains and has some of the few [[steam locomotive]]s still in service in [[India]].\n\nDarjeeling has several British-style [[Private school (India and Sri Lanka)|private schools]], which attract pupils from all over India and a few neighbouring countries. The varied culture of the town reflects its diverse demographic milieu comprising [[Lepcha people|Lepcha]], Khampa, [[Indian Gorkha|Gorkha]], [[Newar]], [[Sherpa people|Sherpa]], [[Bhutia]], [[Bengalis|Bengali]]<ref name=\"Culture\"/> and other mainland Indian ethno-linguistic groups. Darjeeling, alongside its neighbouring town of [[Kalimpong]], was the centre of the [[Gorkhaland]] [[social movement]] in the 1980s and summer 2017.\n{{TOC left}}\n{{Clear left}}\n\n==Toponymy==\nThe name Darjeeling comes from the [[Standard Tibetan|Tibetan]] words ''Dorje'', which is the [[Vajra|thunderbolt sceptre]] of the Hindu deity [[Indra]], and ''ling'', which means \"a place\" or \"land\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Pre-Independence [Darjeeling]|url=http://darjeeling.gov.in/darj-hist.html|publisher=[[Darjeeling district|Government of Darjeeling]]|accessdate=17 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031114710/http://darjeeling.gov.in/darj-hist.html|archivedate=31 October 2015}}</ref>\n{{OSM Location map\n| width=420| height=450| zoom=13\n| coord={{coord|27|2|0|N|88|16|3|E}}| float=left|caption='''Darjeeling'''<br/> TE: tea estate, F: facility, T: religious place, I: institute<br/>Abbreviations used in names \u2013 TE for Tea Estate<br/>Owing to space constraints in the small map, the actual locations in a larger map may vary slightly<br/>All places marked in the map are linked in the larger full screen map\n|mark-coord1={{coord|27|2|45|N|88|15|31|E}} | label-pos1=left|label1= Happy Valley TE| numbered1=TE| mark-title1= [[Happy Valley Tea Estate]] (TE)|label-color1= #800000 |label-size1=11| mark-size1=12|shape1=l-circle| shape-color1=#87A96B |shape-outline1=white|label-offset-x1=2\n|mark-coord2={{coord|27|2|20|N|88|14|58|E}} | label-pos2=left|label2=Arya TE| numbered2=TE| mark-title2= [[Arya Tea Estate]] (TE)| shape-color2=#87A96B\n|mark-coord3={{coord|27|2|33|N|88|17|58|E}} | label-pos3=left|label3=Lebong & Mineral Spring TE| numbered3=R| mark-title3= [[Lebong & Mineral Spring Tea Garden]] (TE)| shape-color3=#87A96B\n|mark-coord4={{coord|27|2|10|N|88|15|46|E}} | label-pos4=left|label4=Darjeeling railway station| numbered4=F| mark-title4= [[Darjeeling railway station]] (F)| shape-color4= #A40000\n|mark-coord5={{coord|27|2|42|N|88|16|3|E}} | label-pos5=right|label5=Chowrasta | numbered5=F| mark-title5= [[Chowrasta (Darjeeling)]] (F)| shape-color5= #A40000\n|mark-coord6={{coord|27|2|52|N|88|16|4|E}} | label-pos6=left|label6=Mahakal Temple| numbered6=T| mark-title6= [[Mahakal Temple, Darjeeling]] (T)| shape-color6= #C42222\n|mark-coord7={{coord|27|3|0|N|88|15|57|E}} | label-pos7=right|label7=Observatory Hill View Point| numbered7=F| mark-title7= [[Observatory Hill, Darjeeling]] (F)| shape-color7= #A40000\n|mark-coord8={{coord|27|3|6|N|88|15|46|E}} | label-pos8=left|label8=Raj Bhavan| numbered8=F| mark-title8= [[Raj Bhavan, Darjeeling]] (F)| shape-color8= #A40000\n|mark-coord9={{coord|27|3|15|N|88|15|15|E}} | label-pos9=right|label9=Padmaja Naidu Himalayan Zoological Park| numbered9=F| mark-title9= [[Padmaja Naidu Himalayan Zoological Park]] (F)| shape-color9= #A40000\n|mark-coord10={{coord|27|3|10|N|88|14|55|E}} | label-pos10=left|label10=Himalayan |labela10=Mountaineering|labelb10=Institute |numbered10=I| mark-title10= [[Himalayan Mountaineering Institute]] (i)| shape-color10= #87410E\n|mark-coord11={{coord|27|3|40|N|88|15|13|E}} | label-pos11=left|label11=Darjeeling Ropeway | numbered11=F| mark-title11= [[Darjeeling Ropeway]] (F)| shape-color11= #A40000\n|mark-coord12={{coord|27|2|40|N|88|15|46|E}} | label-pos12=left|label12= Lloyd\u2019s Botanical Garden| numbered12= F| mark-title12= [[Lloyd's Botanical Garden]] (F)| shape-color12= #A40000\n|mark-coord13={{coord|27|1|39|N|88|15|32|E}} | label-pos13=left|label13= Peace Pagoda| numbered13= T| mark-title13= [[Peace Pagoda, Darjeeling]] (F)| shape-color13= #C42222\n|mark-coord14={{coord|27|1|0|N|88|14|48|E}} | label-pos14=left|label14= Batasia Loop| numbered14= F| mark-title14= [[Batasia Loop]] (F)| shape-color14= #A40000\n|mark-coord15={{coord|27|0|42|N|88|15|1|E}} | label-pos15=left|label15= Ghum Monastery| numbered15= T| mark-title15= [[Ghum Monastery]] (T)| shape-color15= #C42222}}\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Darjeeling}}\n[[File:Bringing in the tea leaf, Darjeeling, 1890.jpg|thumb|Bringing in the Darjeeling tea harvest, circa 1890]]\n[[File:King of Sikkim with a group of Lama, Darjeeling, India, c. 1900.jpg|thumb|The [[King of Sikkim]] in Darjeeling about 1900]]\nThe history of Darjeeling is intertwined with that of [[Sikkim]], [[Nepal]], [[British India]], and [[Bhutan]]. Until the early 19th century, the hilly area around Darjeeling was controlled by the [[Kingdom of Sikkim]]{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|pp=47\u201348}} with the settlement consisting of a few villages of the [[Lepcha people|Lepcha]] and [[Kirati people]].{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=51}} The [[Chogyal]] of Sikkim had been engaged in unsuccessful warfare against the [[Gurkha]]s of Nepal.\n\nFrom 1780, the Gurkhas made several attempts to capture the entire region of Darjeeling. By the beginning of the 19th century, they had overrun Sikkim as far eastward as the [[Teesta River]] and had conquered and annexed the [[Terai]] and the entire area now belonged to Nepal.<ref>{{Cite book | title = 1922 Darjeeling Past and Present \u2013 A Concise History of Darjeeling District since 1835| year = 1922| last = Dozey| first = E. C. |publisher = University of Michigan Library | asin= B00416COE4| page = 2}}</ref> In the meantime, the [[British Army]] was engaged in preventing the [[Gorkhas]] from over-running the whole of the northern frontier. The [[Anglo-Nepalese War]] war broke out in 1814, which resulted in the defeat of the Gurkhas and subsequently led to the signing of the [[Sugauli Treaty]] in 1816. According to the treaty, Nepal had to cede all those territories annexed from the Chogyal of Sikkim to the [[British East India Company]] (i.e. the area between [[Mechi River]] and Teesta River). Later in 1817, through the [[Treaty of Titalia]], the British East India Company reinstated the Chogyal of Sikkim, restored all the tracts of land between the River Mechi and the River Teesta to the Chogyal of Sikkim and guaranteed his sovereignty.<ref name=\"HistoryOfDarjeeling\"/>\n\nIn 1828, a delegation of the British [[East India Company]] (BEIC) officials on its way to the Nepal-Sikkim border stayed in Darjeeling and decided that the region was a suitable site for a sanatorium for British soldiers.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=50}}{{sfn|Lamb|1986|p=69}} The company negotiated a lease of the area west of the [[Mahananda River]] from the Chogyal of Sikkim in 1835.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=47}} In 1849, the BEIC Superintendent [[Archibald Campbell (doctor)|Archibald Campbell]] and the explorer and botanist [[Joseph Dalton Hooker]] were imprisoned in the region by the Sikkim Chogyal. The BEIC sent a force to free them. Continued friction between the BEIC and the Sikkim authorities resulted in the annexation of {{convert|640|mi2|km2|order=flip}} of territory by the British in 1850. In 1864, the Bhutanese rulers and the British signed the [[Treaty of Sinchula]] that ceded the passes leading through the hills and [[Kalimpong]] to the British.<ref name=\"HistoryOfDarjeeling\"/> Further discord between Sikkim and the British resulted in a war, culminating in the signing of a treaty and the annexation by the British of the area east of the Teesta River in 1865.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=48}} By 1866, Darjeeling district had assumed its current shape and size, covering an area of {{convert|1234|mi2|km2|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"HistoryOfDarjeeling\"/>\n[[File:Darjeeling_War_Memorial,_at_Batasia_Loop,_Darjeeling,.jpg|left|thumb|Darjeeling War Memorial |A view of the Darjeeling War Memorial, located at the [[Batasia Loop]] of the [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway]]. Kangchenjunga is visible in the background.]]\n\nDuring the [[British Raj]], Darjeeling's temperate climate led to its development as a [[hill station]] for British residents seeking to escape the summer heat of the plains. The development of Darjeeling as a sanatorium and health resort proceeded briskly.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=51}} Arthur Campbell, a surgeon with the Company, and [[Robert Napier, 1st Baron Napier of Magdala|Lieutenant Robert Napier]] were responsible for establishing a hill station there. Campbell's efforts to develop the station, attract immigrants to cultivate the slopes and stimulate trade resulted in a hundredfold increase in the population of Darjeeling between 1835 and 1849.<ref name=\"HistoryOfDarjeeling\"/>{{sfn|Lamb|1986|p=71}} The first road connecting the town with the plains was constructed between 1839 and 1842.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=51}}{{sfn|Lamb|1986|p=71}} In 1848, a military depot was set up for British soldiers, and the town became a municipality in 1850.{{sfn|Lamb|1986|p=71}} Commercial cultivation of tea in the district began in 1856, and induced a number of British planters to settle there.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=50}} Darjeeling became the formal summer capital of the [[Bengal Presidency]] after 1864.{{sfn|Kenny|1995|p=700}} Scottish [[missionary|missionaries]] undertook the construction of schools and welfare centres for the British residents, laying the foundation for Darjeeling's notability as a centre of education. The opening of the [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway]] in 1881 further hastened the development of the region.<ref name=\"UNESCO-MountainRailways\" /> In 1899, Darjeeling was rocked by major [[landslide]]s that caused severe damage to the town and the native population.{{sfn|Gerard|1990|p=258}}\n\n[[File:Darjeeling (Baedeker, 1914).jpg|thumb|left|Map of the station and its environs, ca 1914]]\nUnder the British Raj, the Darjeeling area was initially a \"Non-Regulation District\", a scheme of administration applicable to economically less advanced districts in the British India; acts and regulations of the British Raj did not automatically apply to the district in line with rest of the country. In 1919, the area was declared a \"backward tract\".<ref name=\"autonomydistrict\">{{cite web | url = http://www.mcrg.ac.in/civilsocietydialogue3.htm | title = Autonomy for Darjeeling: History and Practice | accessdate = 15 June 2011 | first = Sanjoy | last = Borbara | year = 2003 | work = Experiences on Autonomy in East and North East: A Report on the Third Civil Society Dialogue on Human Rights and Peace | publisher = Mahanirban Calcutta Research Group | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110721150332/http://www.mcrg.ac.in/civilsocietydialogue3.htm | archivedate = 21 July 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> During the [[Indian independence movement]], the [[Non-cooperation movement]] spread through the tea estates of Darjeeling.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=60}} There was also a failed assassination attempt by [[Revolutionary movement for Indian independence|revolutionaries]] on [[John Anderson, 1st Viscount Waverley|John Anderson]], the [[Governor of Bengal]] in 1934.<ref name=\"DarjeelingHills-Independence\" /> Subsequently, during the 1940s, [[communist]] activists continued the nationalist movement against the British by mobilising the plantation workers and the peasants of the district.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=61}}\n\n[[File:A Darjeeling street scene, 1880.jpg|thumb|Darjeeling view, 1880]]\nSocio-economic problems of the region that had not been addressed during British Raj continued to linger and were reflected in a representation made to the [[Constituent Assembly of India]] in 1947, which highlighted the issues of regional autonomy and Nepali nationality in Darjeeling and adjacent areas.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=61}} After the [[independence of India]] in 1947, Darjeeling was merged with the state of West Bengal. A separate district of Darjeeling was established consisting of the hill towns of Darjeeling, [[Kurseong]], Kalimpong and some parts of the Terai region. While the hill population comprised mainly ethnic Nepalis, the plains harboured a large ethnic Bengali population who were refugees from the [[Partition of India]].{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=55}} A cautious and non-receptive response by the West Bengal government to most demands of the ethnic Nepali population led to increased calls, in the 1950s and 1960s, for Darjeeling's autonomy and for the recognition of the [[Nepali language]]; the state government acceded to the latter demand in 1961.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|pp=61\u201362}}\n\nThe creation of a new state of Sikkim in 1975, along with the reluctance of the Government of India to recognise Nepali as an official language under the [[Constitution of India]], brought the [[Gorkhaland movement]] to the forefront.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=62}} Agitation for a separate state continued through the 1980s,{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|pp=63\u201364}} included violent protests during the 1986\u201388 period. The agitation ceased only after an agreement between the government and the [[Gorkha National Liberation Front]] (GNLF), resulting in the establishment of an elected body in 1988 called the [[Darjeeling Gorkha Hill Council]] (DGHC), which received autonomy to govern the district. Though Darjeeling became peaceful, the issue of a separate state lingered, fuelled in part by the lack of comprehensive economic development in the region even after the formation of the DGHC.{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=65}} New protests erupted in 2008\u201309, but both the Union and State governments rejected [[Gorkha Janmukti Morcha]]'s (GJM) demand for a separate state.<ref name=\"NewProtest\">{{cite news| url = http://www.livemint.com/2009/07/14124608/Darjeeling-protests-hit-tea-an.html | title = Darjeeling protests hit tea and tourism |newspaper=[[Livemint]] | date =2009 | author =Dhar, S. | accessdate = 25 November 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://archive.today/20121208142845/http://www.livemint.com/2009/07/14124608/Darjeeling-protests-hit-tea-an.html | archivedate = 8 December 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In July 2011, a pact was signed between GJM, the Government of West Bengal and the Government of India which includes the formation of a new autonomous, elected [[Gorkhaland Territorial Administration]] (GTA), a hill council endowed with more powers than its predecessor Darjeeling Gorkha Hill Council.<ref>{{cite news |title=Darjeeling tripartite pact signed for Gorkhaland Territorial Administration |author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Darjeeling-tripartite-pact-signed-for-Gorkhaland-Territorial-Administration/articleshow/9263963.cms |newspaper=Times of India |date=18 July 2011 |accessdate=29 July 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120724010152/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Darjeeling-tripartite-pact-signed-for-Gorkhaland-Territorial-Administration/articleshow/9263963.cms |archivedate=24 July 2012  }}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Mt. Kanchenjunga.jpg|thumb|right|View of [[Kangchenjunga|Kanchengjunga]] as seen from Darjeeling]]\nDarjeeling is the main town of the [[Darjeeling Sadar|Sadar]] subdivision and also the headquarters of the district. It is located at an elevation of {{cvt|6700|ft|m|order=flip}}<ref name=\"DistProf\" /> in the [[Darjeeling Himalayan hill region]] on the Darjeeling-Jalapahar range that originates in the south from [[Ghum, West Bengal|Ghum]]. The range is Y-shaped with the base resting at [[Katapahar]] and [[Jalapahar]] and two arms diverging north of the [[Observatory Hill, Darjeeling|Observatory Hill]]. The north-eastern arm dips suddenly and ends in the [[Lebong]] spur, while the north-western arm passes through North Point and ends in the valley near [[Tukver Tea Estate]].<ref name=\"urbanmanagement\">{{cite web\n| first = Vimal | last = Khawas | year = 2003 | url = http://www.mtnforum.org/resources/library/khawv03e.htm | title = Urban Management in Darjeeling Himalaya: A Case Study of Darjeeling Municipality | publisher = The Mountain Forum | accessdate = 1 May 2006| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041020031749/http://www.mtnforum.org/resources/library/khawv03e.htm |archivedate=20 October 2004 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The hills are nestled within higher peaks and the snow-clad Himalayan ranges tower over the town in the distance. [[Kanchenjunga]], the world's third-highest peak, {{cvt|8598|m|ft}} high, is the most prominent mountain visible. On clear days Nepal's [[Mount Everest]], {{cvt|29035|ft|m|order=flip}} high, can be seen.<ref name=\"britannica\">{{cite web | url = http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9028781 | title = Darjeeling | accessdate = 26 July 2006 | encyclopedia = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica | publisher = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Premium Service }}</ref>\n\nThe hills of Darjeeling are part of the [[Lesser Himalaya]]. The soil is chiefly composed of [[sandstone]] and conglomerate formations, which are the solidified and upheaved detritus of the great range of [[Himalaya]]. However, the soil is often poorly consolidated (the permeable sediments of the region do not retain water between rains) and is not considered suitable for agriculture. The area has steep slopes and loose [[topsoil]], leading to frequent landslides during the [[monsoon]]s. According to the [[Bureau of Indian Standards]], the town falls under [[Earthquake hazard zoning of India|seismic zone-IV]], (on a scale of I to V, in order of increasing proneness to earthquakes) near the [[convergent boundary]] of the [[India Plate|Indian]] and the [[Eurasian Plate|Eurasian]] [[tectonic plate]]s and is subject to frequent earthquakes.<ref name=\"britannica\" />\n\n=== Climate ===\n{{Weather box\n| location = Darjeeling (1981\u20132010, extremes 1901\u20132012)\n| metric first = yes\n| single line = yes\n| Jan record high C = 18.9\n| Feb record high C = 19.2\n| Mar record high C = 24.0\n| Apr record high C = 26.7\n| May record high C = 25.7\n| Jun record high C = 27.7\n| Jul record high C = 28.0\n| Aug record high C = 28.5\n| Sep record high C = 27.5\n| Oct record high C = 26.0\n| Nov record high C = 24.5\n| Dec record high C = 20.0\n| year record high C = 28.5\n| Jan high C = 10.7\n| Feb high C = 12.4\n| Mar high C = 15.6\n| Apr high C = 18.5\n| May high C = 19.3\n| Jun high C = 19.8\n| Jul high C = 19.6\n| Aug high C = 20.0\n| Sep high C = 19.8\n| Oct high C = 19.5\n| Nov high C = 17.1\n| Dec high C = 14.0\n| year high C = 17.2\n| Jan low C = 1.5\n| Feb low C = 2.9\n| Mar low C = 5.7\n| Apr low C = 8.8\n| May low C = 10.6\n| Jun low C = 12.8\n| Jul low C = 13.4\n| Aug low C = 13.4\n| Sep low C = 12.4\n| Oct low C = 10.5\n| Nov low C = 6.3\n| Dec low C = 3.8\n| year low C = 8.5\n| Jan record low C = -7.2\n| Feb record low C = -6.4\n| Mar record low C = -4.8\n| Apr record low C = 0.0\n| May record low C = 1.4\n| Jun record low C = 6.6\n| Jul record low C = 3.9\n| Aug record low C = 8.0\n| Sep record low C = 6.2\n| Oct record low C = 3.2\n| Nov record low C = -4.4\n| Dec record low C = -4.6\n| year record low C = -7.2\n| rain colour = green\n| Jan rain mm = 13.5\n| Feb rain mm = 14.0\n| Mar rain mm = 30.8\n| Apr rain mm = 76.9\n| May rain mm = 137.9\n| Jun rain mm = 466.0\n| Jul rain mm = 656.7\n| Aug rain mm = 528.2\n| Sep rain mm = 379.7\n| Oct rain mm = 59.1\n| Nov rain mm = 14.4\n| Dec rain mm = 2.9\n| year rain mm = 2380.0\n| Jan rain days = 1.1\n| Feb rain days = 1.5\n| Mar rain days = 2.8\n| Apr rain days = 6.8\n| May rain days = 10.5\n| Jun rain days = 18.8\n| Jul rain days = 22.9\n| Aug rain days = 21.7\n| Sep rain days = 14.9\n| Oct rain days = 2.9\n| Nov rain days = 0.6\n| Dec rain days = 0.7\n| year rain days = 105.3\n|time day = 17:30 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| Jan humidity = 81\n| Feb humidity = 78\n| Mar humidity = 75\n| Apr humidity = 78\n| May humidity = 88\n| Jun humidity = 93\n| Jul humidity = 94\n| Aug humidity = 92\n| Sep humidity = 90\n| Oct humidity = 84\n| Nov humidity = 75\n| Dec humidity = 74\n|year humidity = 84\n| Jan sun = 167.4\n| Feb sun = 141.3\n| Mar sun = 145.7\n| Apr sun = 147.0\n| May sun = 151.9\n| Jun sun = 72.0\n| Jul sun = 77.5\n| Aug sun = 102.3\n| Sep sun = 96.0\n| Oct sun = 167.4\n| Nov sun = 189.0\n| Dec sun = 189.1\n|year sun = \n| Jand sun = 5.4\n| Febd sun = 5.0\n| Mard sun = 4.7\n| Aprd sun = 4.9\n| Mayd sun = 4.9\n| Jund sun = 2.4\n| Juld sun = 2.5\n| Augd sun = 3.3\n| Sepd sun = 3.2\n| Octd sun = 5.4\n| Novd sun = 6.3\n| Decd sun = 6.1\n|yeard sun = 4.5\n|source 1 = [[India Meteorological Department]]<ref name=IMDnormals>\n{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200205040301/http://imdpune.gov.in/library/public/1981-2010%20CLIM%20NORMALS%20%28STATWISE%29.pdf\n| archivedate = 5 February 2020\n| url = http://imdpune.gov.in/library/public/1981-2010%20CLIM%20NORMALS%20%28STATWISE%29.pdf\n| title = Station: Darjeeling Climatological Table 1981\u20132010\n| work = Climatological Normals 1981\u20132010\n| publisher = India Meteorological Department\n| date = January 2015\n| pages = 227\u2013228\n| accessdate = 18 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=IMDextremes>\n{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200205042509/http://imdpune.gov.in/library/public/EXTREMES%20OF%20TEMPERATURE%20and%20RAINFALL%20upto%202012.pdf\n| archivedate = 5 February 2020\n| url = http://imdpune.gov.in/library/public/EXTREMES%20OF%20TEMPERATURE%20and%20RAINFALL%20upto%202012.pdf\n| title = Extremes of Temperature & Rainfall for Indian Stations (Up to 2012)\n| publisher = India Meteorological Department\n| date = December 2016\n| page = M233\n| accessdate = 17 February 2020}}</ref>\n|source 2 = [[Deutscher Wetterdienst]] (sun 1891\u20131990)<ref name = DWD>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.dwd.de/DWD/klima/beratung/ak/ak_422950_kt.pdf\n| title = Klimatafel von Darjeeling, West Bengal / Indische Union\n| work = Baseline climate means (1961\u20131990) from stations all over the world\n| publisher = Deutscher Wetterdienst\n| language = German\n| accessdate = 19 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nDarjeeling has a [[temperate|temperate climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Cwb'',<ref name=\"Climate-Data.org\">{{cite web |url=http://en.climate-data.org/location/33809/ |title=Climate graph, Temperature graph, Climate table |publisher=Climate-Data.org |accessdate=30 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001173425/http://en.climate-data.org/location/33809/ |archivedate=1 October 2015  }}</ref> [[subtropical highland climate]]) with wet summers caused by [[Monsoon of South Asia|monsoon rains]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Malley|first=L.S.S. O|title=Bengal District Gazetteer : Darjeeling|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LhOzszXcM9UC&pg=PA15|origyear=1907|year=1999|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|isbn=978-81-7268-018-3|pages=15\u201316|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509151511/https://books.google.com/books?id=LhOzszXcM9UC&pg=PA15|archivedate=9 May 2016}}</ref> The annual mean maximum temperature is {{cvt|14.9|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} while the mean minimum temperature is {{cvt|8.9|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}},<ref name=\"DistProf\" /> with monthly mean temperatures ranging from {{cvt|6|to|18|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}.<ref name=\"Climate-Data.org\"/> The lowest temperature recorded was {{cvt|-5|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} on 11 February 1905.<ref name=\"DistProf\" /> The average annual precipitation is {{cvt|3092|mm}}, with an average of 126 days of rain in a year.<ref name=\"DistProf\" /> The highest rainfall occurs in July.<ref name=IMDnormals/><ref name=\"Climate-Data.org\"/> The heavy and concentrated rainfall that is experienced in the region, aggravated by deforestation and haphazard planning, often causes devastating landslides, leading to loss of life and property.{{sfn|Sarkar|1999|p=299}}<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/brewtal-climate-droughts-storms-cracking-darjeeling-s-teacup/story-y2qbtBZmpNE2SLeWnmQdQK.html | title = Brewtal climate: Droughts, storms cracking Darjeeling's teacup | work = [[Hindustan Times]] | date = 26 November 2009 | author = Malabi Gupta | accessdate = 30 September 2015 | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151001180130/http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/brewtal-climate-droughts-storms-cracking-darjeeling-s-teacup/story-y2qbtBZmpNE2SLeWnmQdQK.html | archivedate = 1 October 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Though not very common, the town receives snow at least once during two winter months of December and January.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.darjeeling-tourism.com/darj_0000b7.htm |title=Darjeeling Weather & Best Time to Visit |accessdate=15 January 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116182734/https://www.darjeeling-tourism.com/darj_0000b7.htm |archivedate=16 January 2017  }}</ref>\n\n== Flora and fauna ==\n[[File:Teagardensvalley.jpg|thumb|Tea plantations in Darjeeling]]\nDarjeeling is a part of the [[Eastern Himalaya]]n zoo-geographic zone.{{sfn|Negi|1992|p=185}} Flora around Darjeeling comprises [[Shorea robusta|sal]], [[oak]], semi-evergreen, [[Temperate broadleaf and mixed forest|temperate]] and [[alpine plant|alpine]] forests.{{sfn|Negi|1992|pp=28\u201329}} Dense evergreen forests of sal and oak lie around the town, where a wide variety of rare [[orchids]] are found. The [[Lloyd's Botanical Garden]] preserves common and rare species of plants, while the [[Padmaja Naidu Himalayan Zoological Park]] specialises in conserving and breeding endangered Himalayan species.<ref name=\"zoo\">{{cite web | url = http://www.hindu.com/2009/10/29/stories/2009102957821300.htm | title = Himalayan Tahrs, Blue sheep for Darjeeling Zoo arrive from Japan | work = [[The Hindu]] | date = 29 October 2009 | accessdate = 10 November 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121107112906/http://www.hindu.com/2009/10/29/stories/2009102957821300.htm | archivedate = 7 November 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The town of Darjeeling and surrounding region face [[deforestation]] due to increasing demand for wood fuel and timber, as well as air pollution from increasing vehicular traffic.<ref name=\"teri\">{{cite web\n |author=TERI\n |year=2001\n |url=http://static.teriin.org/reports/rep17/rep17.pdf\n |title=Sustainable Development in the Darjeeling Hill Area\n |page=20\n |publisher=Tata Energy Research Institute, New Delhi. (TERI Project No.2000UT64)\n |accessdate=1 May 2006\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060623100515/http://static.teriin.org/reports/rep17/rep17.pdf\n |archivedate=23 June 2006\n }}</ref>\n\nForests and wildlife in the district are managed and protected by the [[Divisional Forest Officer]] of the Territorial and Wildlife wing of the West Bengal Forest Department.{{sfn|Negi|1992|p=185}} The fauna found in Darjeeling includes several species of [[duck]]s, [[Eurasian Teal|teals]], [[plover]]s and [[gull]]s that pass Darjeeling while migrating to and from [[Tibet]].{{sfn|Mackintosh|2009|p=2}} Small mammals found in the region include [[small Indian civet]]s, [[mongoose]]s and [[badger]]s.{{sfn|Negi|1992|pp=43\u201348}} TA conservation centre for [[red panda]]s opened at Darjeeling Zoo in 2014, building on a prior captive breeding program.<ref name=\"panda\" />\n\n== Civic administration ==\n[[File:Darjeeling Municipality.JPG|thumb|Darjeeling Municipality Building]]\nThe Darjeeling urban agglomeration consists of [[Darjeeling Municipality]] and the Tukvar Tea Garden (Tukvar valley).<ref name=\"census1\">{{cite web\n| publisher = Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal | url = http://www.wbcensus.gov.in/DataTables/02/FrameTable4_1.htm | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20050827091947/http://www.wbcensus.gov.in/DataTables/02/FrameTable4_1.htm | archivedate = 27 August 2005 | title = Table-4 Population, Decadal Growth Rate, Density and General Sex Ratio by Residence and Sex, West Bengal/ District/ Sub District, 1991 and 2001 | year = 2003 | accessdate = 30 April 2006\n}}</ref> Established in 1850, the Darjeeling municipality maintains the civic administration of the town, covering an area of {{cvt|10.57|km2|sqmi}}.<ref name=\"census1\" /> The municipality consists of a board of councillors elected from each of the 32 [[ward (subnational entity)|wards]] of Darjeeling town as well as a few members nominated by the state government. The board of councillors elects a chairman from among its elected members;<ref name=\"urbanmanagement\" /> the chairman is the executive head of the municipality. The [[Gorkha Janmukti Morcha]] (GJMM) holds power in the municipality {{as of|2011}}.\n\nFrom 1988 to 2012, the Gorkha-dominated hill areas of Darjeeling district were under the jurisdiction of the [[Darjeeling Gorkha Hill Council]] (DGHC). In 2012, the DGHC was replaced by the [[Gorkhaland Territorial Administration]] (GTA). The elected members of this body are authorised to manage certain affairs of the hills, including education, health and tourism. Law and order in Darjeeling town comes under the jurisdiction of the district police force, which is a part of the [[West Bengal Police]]; a [[Deputy Superintendent|Deputy Superintendent of Police]] oversees the town's security and law affairs. Darjeeling municipality area has two police stations at Darjeeling and [[Jorebungalow]].<ref name=\"census2\">\n{{cite web | publisher = Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal | url = http://web.cmc.net.in/wbcensus/DataTables/01/Table-3.htm | title = Table-3 District Wise List of Statutory Towns (Municipal Corporation, Municipality, Notified Area and Cantonment Board), Census Towns and Outgrowths, West Bengal, 2001 | year = 2003 | accessdate=30 April 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721163402/http://web.cmc.net.in/wbcensus/DataTables/01/Table-3.htm|archivedate= 21 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Civil utilities ==\n\n[[File:Mall Road, Darjeeling.JPG|right|thumb|Mall Road]]\nNatural springs in the [[Senchal Lake|Senchal Range]] provide most of Darjeeling's water supply. Water collected is routed through stone conduits to two lakes that were constructed in 1910 and 1932, from where it is piped to the town after purification at the Jorebungalow filtration plant.<ref name=\"Watersupply\" /> During the dry season, when water supplied by springs is insufficient, water is pumped from [[Khong Khola]], a nearby small perennial stream. Increasing demand has led to a worsening shortfall in water supply; just over 50% of the town's households are connected to the municipal water supply system.<ref name=\"urbanmanagement\" /> Various efforts made to augment the water supply, including the construction of a third storage reservoir in 1984, have failed to yield desired results.<ref name=\"Watersupply\" />\n\nThe town has an underground [[sewage system]], covering about 40% of the town area, that collects domestic waste and conveys it to [[septic tank]]s for disposal.<ref name=\"Generalinfo\" /> Solid waste is disposed of in a nearby [[landfill|dumping ground]], which also houses the town's [[crematorium]].<ref name=\"Generalinfo\" /> [[Kerbside collection|Doorstep collection]] of garbage and segregation of biodegradable and non-biodegradable waste have been implemented since 2003.{{sfn|Aftab|2005|p=186}} [[Vermicomposting]] of vegetable waste is carried out with the help of non-governmental organisations.{{sfn|Aftab|2005|p=187}} In June 2009, in order to reduce waste, the municipality proposed a ban on plastic carrier bags and sachets in the town.<ref name=\"Dam2009-06-11\" />\n\nDarjeeling got from 1897 up to the early 1990s [[hydroelectricity]] from the nearby [[Sidrapong Hydel Power Station]], such being the first town in India supplied with hydropower. Today, electricity is supplied by the [[West Bengal State Electricity Board]] from other places. The town often suffers from power outages and the electrical supply voltage is unstable, making [[voltage stabiliser]]s popular with many households. Almost all of the primary schools are now maintained by Darjeeling Gorkha Autonomous Hill Council. The total length of all types of roads within the municipal area is around {{cvt|134|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"Roads\" /> The [[West Bengal Fire Service]] provides emergency services for the town.\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Darjeelingteagardens.jpg|thumb|right|Plucking the tea leaves in the traditional fashion]]\nThe two most significant contributors to Darjeeling's economy are tourism and the tea industry. [[Darjeeling tea]], due to the unique agro-climatic conditions of Darjeeling, has a distinctive natural flavour, is internationally reputed and recognised as a geographical indicator. The office of the [[Indian Tea Association|Darjeeling Indian Tea Association (DITA)]] is located at Darjeeling.{{sfn|Srivastava|2003|p=4024}} Darjeeling produces 7% of India's tea output, approximately {{convert|9000000|kg|lb}} every year.<ref name=\"NewProtest\" /> The tea industry has faced competition in recent years from tea produced in other parts of India as well as other countries like Nepal.<ref name=\"BBC2001-07-27\" /> Widespread concerns about labour disputes, worker layoffs and closing of estates have affected investment and production.<ref name=\"Haber2004-01-14\" /> Several tea estates are being run on a workers' [[cooperative]] model, while others are being planned for conversion into tourist resorts.<ref name=\"Haber2004-01-14\" /> More than 60% of workers in the tea gardens are women.<ref name=\"census1\" /> Besides tea, the most widely cultivated crops include [[maize]], [[millets]], [[rice|paddy]], [[cardamom]], [[potato]] and [[ginger]].<ref name=\"Agriculture\" />\n\nDarjeeling had become an important tourist destination as early as 1860.{{sfn|Lamb|1986|p=71}} It is reported to be the only location in eastern India that witnesses large numbers of foreign tourists.<ref name=\"NewProtest\" /> It is also a popular filming destination for [[Bollywood]] and [[Cinema of West Bengal|Bengali cinema]]. [[Satyajit Ray]] shot his film ''[[Kanchenjungha]]'' (1962) here, and his [[Feluda]] series story, ''Darjeeling Jomjomaat'', was also set in the town. Bollywood movies such as ''[[Aradhana (1969 film)|Aradhana]]'' (1969), ''[[Main Hoon Na]]'' (2004), [[Parineeta (2005 film)|Parineeta]] (2005) and more recently ''[[Barfi!]]'' (2012) have been filmed here.<ref name=\"aradhana1\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.outlooktraveller.com/aspscripts/travelogue.asp?dest=Darjeeling\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070415015159/http://www.outlooktraveller.com/aspscripts/travelogue.asp?dest=Darjeeling\n| archivedate = 15 April 2007\n| title = Darjeeling: Where the journey is the destination\n| accessdate = 9 March 2007\n| author = Sudha Mahalingam\n|date=March 2001\n| work = Outlook Traveller\n| publisher = Outlook Publishing (India) Private Limited\n}}</ref><ref name=\"aradhana2\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.indialine.com/travel/trains/darjeeling-toy-train.html\n |title       = Darjeeling Toy Train\n |accessdate  = 5 December 2009\n |work        = Theme India: Train Tourism in India\n |publisher   = IndiaLine\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100507123327/http://www.indialine.com/travel/trains/darjeeling-toy-train.html\n |archivedate = 7 May 2010\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n== Tourism ==\nTourist inflow into Darjeeling had been affected by the political instability in the region, and agitations in the 1980s and 2000s hit the tourism industry hard.<ref name=\"NewProtest\" />{{sfn|Dasgupta|1999|p=66}} However, since 2012, Darjeeling has once again witnessed a steady inflow of both domestic and international tourists. Presently, around 50,000 foreign and 500,000 domestic tourists visit Darjeeling each year,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Darjeeling hills showing highly positive tourist inflow picture|url = http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-05-24/news/39502040_1_legendary-toy-train-festive-season-eastern-himalayan-tour|website = timesofindia-economictimes|accessdate = 30 December 2015}}</ref> and its repute as the \"Queen of the Hills\" remains unaltered. According to an ''India Today'' survey published on 23 December 2015, Darjeeling is the third most Googled travel destination among all the tourist destinations in India. Even though there are political instabilities in Darjeeling, its tourism rate is increasing year by year. Many visit this place for food specialities like momos, steamed stick rice, and other steamed foods famous in this region, as well as to see the natural beauty of the area.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Top 10 Indian destinations searched on Google in 2015 : Plus List, News - India Today|url = http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/top-10-indian-destinations-searched-on-google-in-2015-udaipur-nainital-darjeeling-kashmir-varanasi/1/554000.html|website = indiatoday.intoday.in|accessdate = 30 December 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151231205355/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/top-10-indian-destinations-searched-on-google-in-2015-udaipur-nainital-darjeeling-kashmir-varanasi/1/554000.html|archivedate = 31 December 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Transport ==\n{{Main|Transport in Darjeeling}}\n[[File:Darjeeling Himalayan Railway.jpg|alt=A train, hauled by a steam locomotive, running beside a road between two rows of buildings with a few people walking on the road.|thumb|left|The narrow gauge train often crisscrosses the street]]\n[[File:Toy train of darjeeling.JPG|thumb|Darjeeling \"Toy Train\"]]Darjeeling can be reached by the {{cvt|88|km|mi}} long [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway]] from [[New Jalpaiguri]], or by [[National Highway 55 (India)|National Highway 55]], from [[Siliguri]], {{cvt|77|km|mi}} away.{{sfn|de Bruyn|Bain|Venkatraman|Joshi|2008|p=578}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhai.org/Doc/project-offer/Highways.pdf |title=NH wise Details of NH in respect of Stretches entrusted to NHAI |publisher=National Highways Authority of India |accessdate=7 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225142615/http://www.nhai.org/Doc/project-offer/Highways.pdf |archivedate=25 February 2009  }}</ref> The Darjeeling Himalayan Railway is a {{cvt|600|mm|ft|0}} [[narrow-gauge railway]] that was declared a [[World Heritage Site]] by [[UNESCO]] in 1999 for being \"an outstanding example of the influence of an innovative transportation system on the social and economic development of a multi-cultural region, which was to serve as a model for similar developments in many parts of the world\",<ref name=\"UNESCO-99report\" /> becoming only the second railway in the world to have this honour.<ref name=\"UNESCO-MountainRailways\" /><ref name=\"aradhana1\" /> Bus services and hired vehicles connect Darjeeling with Siliguri and Darjeeling has road connections with [[Bagdogra]], [[Gangtok]] and [[Kathmandu]] and the neighbouring towns of [[Kurseong]] and [[Kalimpong]].{{sfn|de Bruyn|Bain|Venkatraman|Joshi|2008|p=578}} However, road and railway communications often get disrupted in the monsoons because of landslides. The nearest airport is [[Bagdogra Airport]], located {{cvt|90|km|mi}} from Darjeeling.{{sfn|de Bruyn|Bain|Venkatraman|Joshi|2008|p=578}} Within the town, people usually traverse by walking. Residents also use [[motorcycle|two-wheelers]] and hired taxis for travelling short distances. The [[Darjeeling Ropeway]], functional since 1968, was closed in 2003 after an accident killed four tourists.<ref name=\"Statesman20Oct\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.thestatesman.net/page.arcview.php?clid=1&id=53912&usrsess=1\n| title = Darjeeling ropeway mishap kills four\n| accessdate = 30 June 2007\n| work = [[The Statesman (India)|The Statesman]]\n| date = 20 October 2003\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929102947/http://www.thestatesman.net/page.arcview.php?clid=1&id=53912&usrsess=1| archivedate = 29 September 2007}}</ref> It reopened in February 2012.<ref name=reopening>{{cite news|title=Darjeeling ropeway reopens after more than 8 yrs |last=Banerjee |first=Amitava |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news//Darjeeling-ropeway-reopens-after-more-than-8-yrs/Article1-805796.aspx |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=2 February 2012 |accessdate=16 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205224710/http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news//Darjeeling-ropeway-reopens-after-more-than-8-yrs/Article1-805796.aspx |archivedate=5 February 2012  }}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{Main|Demographics of Darjeeling}}\n[[File:Darjeelingflags.jpg|left|thumb|Colourful Buddhist prayer flags around [[Mahakal Temple (Darjeeling)|Mahakal Temple]] at Observatory Hill, Darjeeling.|alt=A man and a woman praying at a small white shrine dedicated to Lord Ganesh. Several colourful flags on buntings are strung across poles in front of the shrine.]]\n[[File:Darjeeling St. Andrew's Church.jpg|thumb|St. Andrew's Church, Darjeeling. Built- 1843, Rebuilt- 1873]]\nAccording to provisional results of [[2011 census of India]], Darjeeling urban agglomeration has a population of 132,016, out of which 65,839 were males and 66,177 were females. The sex ratio is 1,005 females per 1,000 males. The 0\u20136 years population is 7,382. Effective literacy rate for the population older than 6 years is 93.17 per cent.<ref name=2011provuatable>{{cite web | url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | title = Urban agglomerations/cities having population 1 lakh and above | work = Provisional population totals, census of India 2011 | publisher = The registrar general & census commissioner, India | accessdate = 12 February 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111113152754/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | archivedate = 13 November 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2001 census, the Darjeeling urban agglomeration, with an area of {{cvt|12.77|km2|sqmi}}, had a population of 109,163, while the municipal area had a population of 107,530.<ref name=census1/> The population density of the municipal area was {{convert|10,173|PD/km2}}. The sex ratio was 1,017 females per 1,000 males,<ref name=census1/> which was higher than the national average of 933 females per 1000 males.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/India_at_glance/fsex.aspx |title=India at a Glance: Sex Ratio |work=Census of India, 2001 |accessdate=19 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091113231934/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/India_at_Glance/fsex.aspx |archivedate=13 November 2009  }}</ref> [[Gorkhas]], speaking [[Nepali language|Nepali]] as native language, form the majority which includes indigenous ethnic groups such as the [[Bhutia]], [[Chhetri]], [[Gurung]], [[Lepcha people|Lepcha]], [[Limbu]], [[Magars|Magar]], [[Newar]]s, [[Rai people|Rai]], [[Sherpa (people)|Sherpa]], [[Tamang]], [[Yolmo people|Yolmo]], along with several other denominations under the Indo-Aryan [[Khas people|Khas]] and the Mongoloid [[Kirata|Kirats]]. Other communities that inhabit Darjeeling include the [[Anglo-Indian]]s, [[Bengalis]], [[Bihari people|Biharis]], [[Chinese people|Chinese]], [[Marwaris]], [[Rajbongshi people|Rajbanshis]] and [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]]. The prevailing languages are [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[Hindi]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and [[English language|English]]. Bengali is prevalent in the plains while Tibetan is used by the refugees and some tribal people.<ref name=\"Culture\">{{cite web|url=http://darjeeling.gov.in/people.html|title=People And Culture|publisher=Official webpage of Darjeeling District|accessdate=26 November 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225153402/http://darjeeling.gov.in/people.html|archivedate=25 December 2008}}</ref> [[Dzongkha]] is spoken by the Bhutias and the Tibetans.\n\nDarjeeling has seen a significant growth in its population, its decadal growth rate being 47% between 1991 and 2001.<ref name=census1/> The colonial town was designed for a population of only 10,000, and subsequent growth has created extensive infrastructural and environmental problems. The district's forests and other natural wealth have been adversely affected by an ever-growing population. The official languages of Darjeeling are [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and [[Nepali language|Nepali]].<ref name=nclm50/>\n\n== Religion ==\n[[File:\u0411\u0443\u0434\u0434\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0445\u0440\u0430\u043c \u0432 \u0414\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0436\u0438\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0435. \u0421\u0438\u043a\u043a\u0438\u043c.jpg|thumb|''Buddhist Temple in Darjiling. Sikkim'', by [[Vasily Vereshchagin]] (1874)]]\nThe predominant religions of Darjeeling are [[Shaivism|Shaivite]] [[Hinduism]] and [[Vajrayana|Vajrayana Buddhism]], followed by [[Christianity]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.census2011.co.in/data/religion/district/1-darjiling-.html |title=Darjiling District Religion Data - Census 2011 |accessdate=10 January 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822042654/http://www.census2011.co.in/data/religion/district/1-darjiling-.html |archivedate=22 August 2017  }}</ref> Indigenous communities such as the [[Lepcha people|Lepchas]], the [[Limbu people|Limbus]], and many others, also practice [[Animism]] and [[Shamanism]] which is very often, but not always, intermixed with the more mainstream [[Hinduism]] and [[Buddhism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Dist_File/datasheet-1901.pdf|title=Basic data sheet, District Darjiling|work=Census of India, 2001|accessdate=19 November 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520041256/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Dist_File/datasheet-1901.pdf|archivedate=20 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Dashain]],&nbsp;[[Tihar (festival)|Tihar]], [[Losar]],&nbsp;[[Buddha Jayanti]],&nbsp;[[Christmas]] are the main festivals. Besides, the diverse ethnic populace of the town also celebrates several local festivals.&nbsp;Buddhist ethnic groups which include the [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]], [[Lepcha people|Lepchas]], [[Bhutia]]s, [[Sherpa people|Sherpas]], [[Hyolmo people|Yolmos]], [[Gurung people|Gurungs]], and [[Tamang people|Tamangs]] celebrate&nbsp;their new year,&nbsp;called&nbsp;Losar,&nbsp;in January/February,&nbsp;[[Maghe Sankranti]], [[Chotrul Duchen]] and [[Tendong Lho Rumfaat]]. The&nbsp;[[Kiranti]]&nbsp;Rai people (Khambus) celebrate their annual&nbsp;[[Sakela]]&nbsp;festivals of&nbsp;[[Ubhauli]]&nbsp;and [[Udhauli]].&nbsp;[[Deusi]] and Bhaileni are songs performed by men and women respectively, during the festival of Tihar. All these provide a regional distinctness to Darjeeling's local culture from the rest of India.&nbsp;[[Darjeeling Carnival]], initiated by a civil society movement known as The Darjeeling Initiative, is a ten-day carnival held yearly during the winter with portrayal of the Darjeeling Hill's musical and cultural heritage as its central theme.<ref name=\"frontline2003\">{{cite journal | author = S.S. Chattopadhyay | date = December 2003 | title = The spirit of Darjeeling | journal = Frontline | volume = 20 | issue = 25 | url = http://www.hindu.com/fline/fl2025/stories/20031219000306600.htm | accessdate = 1 May 2006 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121107132238/http://www.hindu.com/fline/fl2025/stories/20031219000306600.htm | archivedate = 7 November 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n{{Main|Culture of Darjeeling}}\n[[File:Buddhist Temple Peace Pagoda Darjeeling West Bengal India (7).JPG|thumb|Peace Pagoda at a Buddhist Temple]]\n[[File:Tibetan Refugee Self Help Darjeeling.jpg|thumb|left|[[Tibetan Refugee Self Help Centre]]|alt=A two-storeyed building to the right of a four-storeyed building. A basketball court in the foreground and a couple of vehicles parked on either side. Foggy atmosphere, with trees in the background.]]\nThe culture of Darjeeling is diverse and includes a variety of indigenous practices and festivals as mentioned above. Many of the [[Nepali Indian|Nepali]] [[Hinduism|Hindus]], as well as the various Buddhist and other ethnic groups such as the Lepchas, Bhutias, Kiranti Limbus, Tibetans, Yolmos, Gurungs, and Tamangs, have their own distinct languages and cultures and yet share a largely harmonious co-existence.\n\nColonial architecture characterizes many buildings in Darjeeling, exemplified by several [[mock Tudor]] residences, [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] churches, the [[Raj Bhavan, Darjeeling|Raj Bhawan]], [[Darjeeling Planters' Club|Planters' Club]] and various educational institutions. [[Buddhist]] monasteries showcase the [[pagoda]] style architecture. Darjeeling is regarded as a centre of music and a niche for musicians and music admirers. Singing and playing musical instruments are common pastimes among the resident population, who take pride in the traditions and role of music in cultural life.<ref name=\"naturecentric\">{{cite web | url = http://ignca.nic.in/cd_07011.htm | title = The Nature-centric Culture of the Nepalese | accessdate = 31 July 2006 | author = D. P. Rasaily | author2 = R. P. Lama | work = The Cultural Dimension of Ecology | publisher = Indira Gandhi National Centre for the Arts, New Delhi | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060715224122/http://ignca.nic.in/cd_07011.htm | archivedate = 15 July 2006 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Darjeeling also has a [[Peace Pagoda]] built-in 1992 by the Japanese Buddhist organisation [[Nipponzan Myohoji]].\n\n==Cuisine==\nDue to the varied mix of cultures in Darjeeling, the local and ethnic food of Darjeeling is also quite varied. Rice, noodles, and potatoes seem to make up the dominant part of the cuisine partly due to the cold climate.\nThe most popular local snack food are [[Momo (food)|Momos]], which are steamed flour dumplings with meat or vegetables fillings served piping hot with a side of clear soup and hot homemade tomato sauce. Locals love Alu Dom (Spicy steamed potato curry) and various versions of it are served. For example, they add Wai Wai Mimi instant noodles over a bowl of Alu Dom and call it Alu Mimi.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Baral|first1=Bipin|title=And... The Crossroad|date=2015|publisher=Partridge Publishing|isbn=9781482849868}}</ref>\n\nAnother popular food is [[Thukpa]] which is of Tibetan origins. Thukpa is homemade noodle soup with meat, eggs and/or vegetables.\n[[Kinema]], [[Chhurpi]], Shaphalay, (Tibetan bread stuffed with meat).<ref name=\"People&Culture\" /> Fermented foods and beverages are consumed by a large percentage of the population.{{sfn|Tamang|Sarkar|Hesseltine|1988|p=376}} Fermented foods include preparations of [[soybean]], [[bamboo shoot]]s, milk and [[Sel roti]], which is made from rice.{{sfn|Tamang|Sarkar|Hesseltine|1988|p=375}} Tea (esp. the butter tea) is the most popular delicacy,<ref name=\"People&Culture\" /> Alcoholic beverages include [[Tongba]], ''Jnaard'' and ''[[Chhaang]]'', variations of a local beer made from fermenting [[finger millet]].<ref name=\"People&Culture\" />{{sfn|Tamang|Sarkar|Hesseltine|1988|p=382}}<ref>{{cite book|title=A Tibetan-English Dictionary|publisher=Motilal Banarsidas|year=1881|isbn=978-81-208-0321-3|edition=1987 reprint|page=341|author=H. \u00c4. Jaschke|place=Delhi}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Alu Mimi Darjeeling.jpg|A bowl of Alu Mimi\nFile:Tongba at Hot Stimulating Cafe.jpg|[[Tongba]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Education ==\nThere are 52 primary schools, 67 high schools and 5 colleges in the town.<ref name=\"Generalinfo\" /> Darjeeling's schools are run either by the state government or by private or religious organisations. Schools mainly use English and Nepali as their media of instruction, although there is the option to learn the official language Hindi and the official state language Bengali. The schools are either affiliated with the [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education|ICSE]], the [[Central Board of Secondary Education|CBSE]], or the [[West Bengal Board of Secondary Education]].\n\nHaving been a summer retreat for the British in India, Darjeeling became the place of choice for the establishment of [[Private school (India and Sri Lanka)|public schools]] on the model of [[Eton College|Eton]], [[Harrow School|Harrow]] and [[Rugby School|Rugby]], allowing the children of British officials to obtain an exclusive education.<ref name=\"publicschool1\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/southasia/History/British/HillStations.html\n |title       = \"Hill Stations: Pinnacles of the Raj\". Review article on Dale Kennedy, ''The Magic Mountains: Hill Stations and the British Raj''\n |accessdate  = 30 July 2001\n |first       = Vinay\n |last        = Lal\n |publisher   = UCLA Social Sciences Computing\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20010622150044/http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/southasia/History/British/HillStations.html\n |archivedate = 22 June 2001\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Institutions such as [[Mount Hermon School, Darjeeling|Mount Hermon School]], [[St. Robert's H.S. School]], [[St. Paul's School, Darjeeling|St. Paul's School]], [[St. Joseph's School - North Point, Darjeeling|St. Joseph's School - North Point]], [[Loreto Convent, Darjeeling|Loreto Convent]] are renowned as centres of educational excellence.<ref name=\"edu-institute\" /> Darjeeling has five colleges\u2014[[St Joseph's College, Darjeeling|St. Joseph's College]], [[Southfield College]] (earlier known as Loreto College), [[Darjeeling Government College]], [[Ghoom-Jorebunglow Degree College]] and Sri Ramakrishna B.T. College\u2014all affiliated to the [[University of North Bengal]] in Siliguri.\n\n== Political unrest ==\n* See article [[Gorkhaland]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Chowrasta (Darjeeling)|Chowrasta]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist\n| colwidth = 30em\n| refs =\n<ref name=\"DistProf\">\n{{cite web\n |title       = District Profile\n |work        = Official webpage\n |publisher   = [[Darjeeling district]]\n |url         = http://www.darjeeling.gov.in/dist-prof.html\n |accessdate  = 30 September 2015\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20150817064946/http://darjeeling.gov.in/dist-prof.html\n |archivedate = 17 August 2015\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"HistoryOfDarjeeling\">\n{{cite web\n |title       = History of Darjeeling\n |work        = Official webpage\n |publisher   = [[Darjeeling district]]\n |url         = http://www.darjeeling.gov.in/darj-hist.html\n |accessdate  = 15 June 2011\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110720072136/http://darjeeling.gov.in/darj-hist.html\n |archivedate = 20 July 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DarjeelingHills-Independence\">\n{{cite web\n |title       = Darjeeling Hills plunges into the Independence Movement\n |work        = Official webpage\n |publisher   = [[Darjeeling district]]\n |url         = http://www.darjeeling.gov.in/independence.html\n |accessdate  = 15 June 2011\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110721163153/http://darjeeling.gov.in/independence.html\n |archivedate = 21 July 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Agriculture\">\n{{cite web\n |title       = Agriculture\n |work        = Official webpage\n |publisher   = [[Darjeeling district]]\n |url         = http://www.darjeeling.gov.in/agriculture.html\n |accessdate  = 15 June 2011\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120129052515/http://darjeeling.gov.in/agriculture.html\n |archivedate = 29 January 2012\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"People&Culture\">\n{{cite web\n |title       = People & Culture\n |work        = Official webpage\n |publisher   = [[Darjeeling district]]\n |url         = http://www.darjeeling.gov.in/people.html\n |accessdate  = 15 June 2011\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110721162520/http://darjeeling.gov.in/people.html\n |archivedate = 21 July 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"edu-institute\">\n{{cite web\n |title       = Educational Institutes\n |work        = Official webpage\n |publisher   = [[Darjeeling district]]\n |url         = http://www.darjeeling.gov.in/edu-institute.html\n |accessdate  = 15 June 2011\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110721161617/http://darjeeling.gov.in/edu-institute.html\n |archivedate = 21 July 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<!--darjeelingmunicipality.com recently expired, needs renewal... tbd. may not emerge as an official site (if it really was;) -->\n<ref name=\"Watersupply\">\n{{cite web\n |title=Water Supply\n |work=Official webpage\n |publish