Grammy Awards|2014]]\n|''[[Vida (Draco Rosa album)|Vida]]''\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]]\n|{{Won}}<ref name=Grammy2014>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/22/grammy-winners-list_n_4646243.html|title=Grammy Winners List 2014: Daft Punk, Macklemore, Lorde & More|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n{{end}}\n\n;Latin Grammy Awards\nA [[Latin Grammy Award]] is an accolade by the [[Latin Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences]] to recognize outstanding achievement in the Latin music industry.\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|[[Latin Grammy Awards of 2004|2004]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|\"[[M\u00e1s y M\u00e1s]]\"\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video|Best Music Video]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[Latin Grammy Awards of 2009|2009]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Teatro (Draco Rosa album)|Teatro]]''\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Rock Solo Vocal Album|Best Rock Solo Vocal Album]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video|Best Long Form Music Video]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|[[Latin Grammy Awards of 2013|2013]]\n|\"[[M\u00e1s y M\u00e1s]]\" (feat. [[Ricky Martin]])\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Vida (Draco Rosa album)|Vida]]''\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Pop Vocal Album|Best Contemporary Pop Vocal Album]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[Latin Grammy Awards of 2019|2019]]\n|''Monte Sagrado''\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Rock Album|Best Rock Album]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|\"Hotel De Los Encuentros\"\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video|Best Long Form Music Video]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n;Lo Nuestro Awards\n[[Lo Nuestro Awards]] ({{lang-es|link=no|Premios Lo Nuestro}}) is an awards show honoring the best of [[Latin music (genre)|Latin music]], presented by television network [[Univision]].\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|[[Premio Lo Nuestro 2011|2011]]\n|''Amor Vincit Omnia''\n|Album of the Year: Rock\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Himself\n|Artist of the Year: Rock\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|\"Esto Es Vida\"\n|Song of the Year: Rock\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Biography|Latin music}}\n*[[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=note/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://dracorosa.com Draco Rosa]\n\n{{Draco Rosa|state=collapsed}}{{Menudo|state=autocollapse}}\n{{Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosa, Draco}}\n[[Category:Draco Rosa]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Puerto Rican male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American child singers]]\n[[Category:American multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin music songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Menudo (band) members]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Ponce]]\n[[Category:People from Long Island]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican independence activists]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican rock singers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Rock en Espa\u00f1ol musicians]]\n[[Category:Sony Music Latin artists]]\n[[Category:Singers from Ponce]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Puerto Rican singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Spanish name|Rosa|Su\u00e1rez}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Draco Rosa\n| image               = DracoRosa3.jpg\n| caption             = Draco on the set of his music video for \"M\u00e1s y M\u00e1s\" in 2013\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Draco Cornelius Rosa Su\u00e1rez<ref name=nameDOB>[https://www.sunsigns.org/famousbirthdays/d/profile/draco-rosa/ ''Draco Rosa Biography, Life, Interesting Facts.''] SunSigns.org  Accessed 1 August 2019.</ref>\n| alias               = {{flatlist|\n* Robi Draco Rosa\n* Robi Rosa\n* Draco\n* Ian Blake {{small|(or Mr. Blake)}}\n* Dolores del Infante {{small|(in 1999)}}\n* Draco Rosa\n* Robi Star\n* Cornelius\n}}\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1970|06|27}}<ref name=nameDOB/><ref>[https://www.latinousa.org/2013/10/11/draco-rosa-lucha-y-vida/ ''Draco Rosa: Lucha y Vida.''] Latino USA. Futuro Media Group. 11 October 2013. Accessed 1 August 2019.</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[Long Island]], New York, US\n| origin              = [[Pe\u00f1uelas, Puerto Rico|Pe\u00f1uelas]], [[Puerto Rico]]<br>[[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]], [[Puerto Rico]]\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n* [[rock en espa\u00f1ol]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[art rock]]\n* [[experimental rock]]\n* [[psychedelic rock]]\n* [[indie rock]]\n* [[Electronic music|electronic]] {{small|(as Mr. Blake)}}\n}}\n| occupation          = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n* poet\n* entrepreneur\n* composer\n}}\n| instrument          = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n* bass\n* piano\n* drums\n}}\n| years_active        = 1984\u2013present\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n* [http://phvx.com/ Phantom Vox]\n* [[Sony Music Latin|Sony Latin]]\n* [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n* Phantom Vox Corp\n}}\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]]\n* [[Maggie's Dream]]\n* [[Ricky Martin]]\n* [[Desmond Child]]\n* [[Ednita Nazario]]\n* [[Rene Perez]]\n* [[Enrique Bunbury|Bunbury]]\n* [[Ruben Blades]]\n* [[Shakira]]\n}}\n| website             = {{URL|dracorosa.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Draco Cornelius Rosa Su\u00e1rez''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8d\u027eako ko\u027e\u02c8neljus \u02c8rosa \u02c8swa\u027ees|lang}}; born '''Robert Edward Rosa Su\u00e1rez''', June 27, 1970<ref>[https://famousbiographies.org/draco-rosa-biography/ ''Draco Rosa Biography.''] Famous Biographies. 2019. Accessed 1 August 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/artist/draco-rosa-mn0001329044/discography ''Draco Rosa.''] Jason Birchmeier. 2019. Accessed 1 August 2019.</ref>), also known as '''Draco Rosa, Robi Draco Rosa''' or simply '''Draco''', is a multiple-time [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] and [[Latin Grammy Award|Latin Grammy]] winning American-born [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] musician, singer, songwriter, composer, multi-instrumentalist, dancer, record producer and entrepreneur.\n\nRosa originally garnered fame as a member of boy band [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]] in the 1980s, singing lead on the band's biggest stateside hit, \"Hold Me\" and featuring prominently in the accompanying music video. After leaving the band he moved to Brazil where he released two albums, achieving mainstream success. Following a brief subsequent stint in California, he returned to New York and joined the band [[Maggie's Dream]], which split after only one album, allowing him to resume his solo career. The singer and composer has released numerous albums, and has composed multiple songs for [[Ednita Nazario]], [[Julio Iglesias]] and former Menudo band-mate, [[Ricky Martin]]. He has also been featured on [[VH1]]'s ''[[Behind the Music]]''.\n\nRosa has been highly influenced by the works of [[Bob Dylan]], [[Miles Davis]], [[Iggy Pop]], [[Jimi Hendrix]], [[Johnny Cash]], [[Luis Alberto Spinetta]], [[The Doors]], [[Camar\u00f3n de la Isla]], [[Horacio Quiroga]], [[Caetano Veloso]], [[Glenn Danzig]], [[Edgar Allan Poe]] and [[Jim Morrison]].\n\nIn 1988, at age 18, he made his motion picture debut in the film ''[[Salsa (1988 film)|Salsa]]'', which was a big hit in Puerto Rico. During the filming of the movie, he met actress [[Angela Alvarado]] who would later become his wife.\n\nIn 1996, he released the Latino alternative rock album ''[[Vagabundo]]'' produced by [[Phil Manzanera]] before helping launch [[Ricky Martin]]'s musical career into a new global setting with ''[[Vuelve (album)|Vuelve]]''. Rosa wrote and produced various of Martin's hit singles including \"[[Mar\u00eda (Ricky Martin song)|Mar\u00eda]]\", \"[[Livin' la Vida Loca]]\", \"[[She's All I Ever Had]]\", \"[[The Cup of Life]]\", \"[[She Bangs]]\" and \"[[Shake Your Bon-Bon]]\", among others. Rosa toured with [[Lenny Kravitz]] during the summer of 2004 to promote his concept album ''[[Mad Love (Robi Draco Rosa album)|Mad Love]]''.\n\nIn April 2011, Rosa was diagnosed with a non-Hodgkin lymphoma cancer near his liver. He underwent alternative and traditional treatment in [[Houston]] and [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]]. This kept Rosa in a hiatus for almost a year until his return in March 2012, when he started recording his latest album with ''[[Vida (Draco Rosa album)|Vida]]'', and gave a concert with [[Juan Luis Guerra]] and [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]] at the [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot Coliseum|Coliseo de Puerto Rico Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot]]. In December 2012, he was declared cancer-free. On December 9, 2013, Rosa's manager confirmed his cancer had relapsed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin-notas/5820005/draco-rosa-faces-a-new-challenge-as-cancer-returns|title=Draco Rosa 'Faces A New Challenge' as Cancer Returns|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> and overcame cancer once again after a second bone marrow transplant, but had to remain in quarantine for four additional months.<ref name=VocesHuff>{{cite web|url=http://voces.huffingtonpost.com/2014/02/05/draco-rosas-libre-cancer-nuevo-transplante-medula-_n_4731931.html|title=Draco: libre de c\u00e1ncer y listo para un nuevo transplante de m\u00e9dula|work=HuffPost Voces|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> As of February, 2019, Rosa has been cancer-free for five years.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Early years (1980s)===\nAt a young age, Rosa moved with his family to Puerto Rico where he spent much of his childhood in the towns of [[Pe\u00f1uelas, Puerto Rico|Pe\u00f1uelas]] and [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]].<ref>[http://www.biography.com/people/draco-rosa-21161421 ''Draco Rosa: Biography.''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016161159/http://www.biography.com/people/draco-rosa-21161421 |date=October 16, 2014 }} Retrieved December 28, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://latinousa.org/2013/10/11/draco-rosa-lucha-y-vida/ ''Draco Rosa: Lucha y Vida.''] October 11, 2013. LatinoUSA. Retrieved February 13, 2014.</ref> In 1984 he joined the increasingly popular [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] boy band [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]]. During much of his tenure with the group, he would share the stage with a young [[Ricky Martin]], which would eventually lead to a musical partnership between the two that proved instrumental in launching Martin's solo career.<ref name=\"BB 27_3_2004\">{{cite web|title=Menudo|magazine=Billboard|via=Internet Archive|date=27 March 2004|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_7w8EAAAAMBAJ|access-date=11 October 2019|page=72}}</ref> As the only member of Menudo who had a native grasp of English, Rosa sang lead vocals on many of the English-language tracks released by the group, including their stateside hit, \"Hold Me\". However, Rosa started to grow disenchanted with the band, particularly after he was denied the opportunity to write songs for them.<ref>[http://www.biography.com/people/draco-rosa-21161421 ''Draco Rosa: Synopsis.''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016161159/http://www.biography.com/people/draco-rosa-21161421 |date=October 16, 2014 }} Retrieved February 13, 2014.</ref> Rosa quit the group in 1987.\n\nAfter moving to Barra Beach, [[Rio de Janeiro]], Rosa spent time with local artists, adding to his musical education. He would go on to release two commercially successful Portuguese-language solo albums in quick succession in the late 1980s.\n\nRosa subsequently moved to Los Angeles where he had gotten the lead-role in the film ''[[Salsa (1988 film)|Salsa]]''. During its filming, Rosa met his future wife, [[Angela Alvarado]]. Like Rosa, Alvarado was also born in New York to Puerto Rican parents. Rosa also appeared alongside [[Christopher Mitchum]] in a German film entitled ''[[Gummib\u00e4rchen k\u00fc\u00dft man nicht]]''. Rosa wrote, produced and performed two songs (\"Angela\" and \"Little Woman\") for the soundtrack of the latter film, which was released by [[RCA Records]] under his publishing company, [[Parque de la Ceiba|Ceiba Tree Music]].\n\nHowever, he would soon move back to his birth state of New York, where he formed the band [[Maggie's Dream]], an [[Funk metal|alternative funk rock/metal]] band who released a self-titled album in 1990 and toured with [[Fishbone]], the [[Black Crowes]] and [[Faith No More]].  A planned follow-up album, ''Elysium'' was recorded in 1992 but never officially released.<ref>[http://rysham.com/site/2015/03/11/lost-gems-of-90s-alt-rock-maggies-dream/ Lost Gems of 90s alt rock - Maggie's Dream - Rysham.com] Retrieved 11-19-2016.</ref>\n\n===Rise to prominence (1990s)===\nIn 1993 a solo contract with [[Sony Music Latin]] enabled Rosa to record in Spain the first of his Spanish-language solo albums, ''[[Frio (album)|Fr\u00edo]]''.\n\nIn between solo projects, Rosa worked on [[Ricky Martin]]'s ''[[A Medio Vivir (album)|A Medio Vivir]]'' under the pseudonym Ian Blake by co-writing and co-producing the majority of the songs on the album,<ref name=\"Draco Rosa.\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmtv.com.ar/biografia/show.php?bnid=257|title=CMTV - Biograf\u00eda de Draco Rosa|website=Cmtv.com.ar|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> including the hit single \"[[Mar\u00eda (Ricky Martin song)|Mar\u00eda]]\", which made it to the Billboard Top 10.\n\nThe 1996 release of his second album, ''[[Vagabundo]]'', recorded in England and produced by [[Roxy Music]] guitarist Phil Manzanera, has been hailed as a \"tour de force of introspective haunting tunes.\"<ref>[http://www.phantomvox.com/draco/bio.html ''Draco Rosa.''] Biografia:English-Espa\u00f1ol. Retrieved February 13, 2014.</ref> The video for the song \"Madre Tierra\", directed by Angela Alvarado, won Best Rock Video in the 1997 [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]];<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Kg8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA74 ''Billboard Latin Music Awards Presented: Regional Mexican.''] Billboard \u2013 May 10, 1997. Vol. 109, No. 19. pp.1,74</ref> ''[[Vagabundo]]'' was included in [[Spin Magazine]]'s 1997 Top 10 list of \"greatest rock en espa\u00f1ol records of all time\".{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' named Rosa to their IT LIST of the 100 most creative people in the entertainment industry.<ref>[http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/32108 ''\"This is a Betrayal\", Ricky Martin's Songwriter Reacts Angrily.''] Diana Baron. January 13, 2001. Retrieved February 13, 2014.</ref>\n\nAn English-language version of ''Fr\u00edo'', entitled ''Songbirds and Roosters'' was released in 1998. As he toured with his songs from ''[[Vagabundo]]'', Rosa wrote and recorded his fellow former Menudo bandmate, [[Ricky Martin]]'s chart-topping album ''[[Vuelve (album)|Vuelve]]'', again under the pseudonym Ian Blake, which resulted in five hit singles including \"[[The Cup of Life]]\" (as well as its Spanish version \"La Copa de la Vida\"). Rosa formed [http://phvx.com/ Phantom Vox Corporation], a multimedia production company that joined Dr\u00e4co Cornelius Music with other writers under Phantom Vox Publishing, the company's subdivision for licensing of original compositions. Phantom Vox Studios, Rosa's own multimedia recording studio and another subdivision of the company, worked as Music Supervisor for ''Livin' the Life'', an independent movie that won the Best Film Award in the 1999 New York Latin Film Fest. Phantom Vox filmed and edited the video for \"Commitment #4,\" a track Rosa composed and recorded in dedication to the [[United States Navy in Vieques, Puerto Rico|removal of the United States Navy in the Puerto Rican island municipality of Vieques]], for bombing training in many parts of the island.\n\n===As a producer (1998\u20132002)===\nBetween 1998 and 1999, Rosa wrote and recorded [[Ricky Martin]]'s [[Ricky Martin (1999 album)|second eponymous album]] and the first in [[English language|English]], which includes the popular single \"[[Livin' la Vida Loca]]\". The album debuted at #1 on the Billboard album charts, selling 22 million copies worldwide. For Martin's follow-up album, ''[[Sound Loaded]]'', Rosa produced four tracks, including the hit single \"[[She Bangs]]\". The album was nominated for the [[Grammy Award]] for Best Pop Vocal Album at the 42nd Grammy Awards. It won the [[American Music Award]] for Favorite Latin Artist and was nominated for the Favorite Pop/Rock Male Artist.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} It was also nominated for the Juno Award for International Album of the Year at the [[Juno Awards of 2000]]. The album has sold over 22 million copies, worldwide.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\nRosa also produced Coraz\u00f3n (1999), the platinum album of [[Ednita Nazario]], for which he also wrote and produced the song \"M\u00e1s Grande Que Grande\" under the name Dolores del Infante, which reached a spot in the Top 10 Latin Billboards for 10 weeks.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}} Coraz\u00f3n was nominated for the 2000 Billboard Latin Music Award for Female Pop Album of the Year. Rosa wrote and produced three songs for singer [[Julio Iglesias]]' album, Noche De Cuatro Lunas (2000).\n\nRosa was one of three singer/songwriters honored in Banco Popular's Christmas Special ''Encuentro'' (2002) alongside [[Juan Luis Guerra]] and [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]].\n\n===Compilation albums and seventh and eighth studio albums (2002\u201308)===\nIn 2002 Rosa released \"Libertad del Alma\", a compilation album which debuted at the top of the Latin Album Billboard chart based only on its sales in Puerto Rico.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jhAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA68 ''Over the Counter: Fresh Start.''] Billboard Magazine. April 17, 2004. Vol. 116, No. 16. p.68.</ref> After two years of experimentation and sessions in studios around the world, Rosa released ''[[Mad Love (Robi Draco Rosa album)|Mad Love]]'' on March 30, 2004. With most songs in English, collaborations with musicians from all over the world and the music videos for \"Dancing in the Rain\" and \"Lie Without a Lover\" (both directed by Angela Alvarado Rosa), Mad Love debuted at #2 on Billboard's Heatseeker charts and was considered the #1 Latin album of 2004 by New York's Newsday. The video for \"[[M\u00e1s y M\u00e1s]]\", also directed by Alvarado, won the [[Latin Grammy Awards of 2004|2004 Latin Grammy Award]] for Best Video.\n\nA few months after the release of Mad Love, Rosa released another compilation album intended specifically for the Latin market titled \"Como Me Acuerdo\", which included four new tracks along with some other songs. He went on an international tour to promote both albums. During the tour he visited several major US cities, as well as Japan, Singapore, England, Spain, Germany, Denmark, Panama, Brazil, Colombia and Argentina, among others.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} In [[Bogota, Colombia]], in particular, he closed the 2004 [[Rock al Parque]], a multitudinous all-day musical extravaganza with a crowd of 150,000 people.<ref>[http://www.infoconcerts.cat/es/concierto/16871/draco ''Draco: Detalles del Concierto.''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222025031/http://www.infoconcerts.cat/es/concierto/16871/draco |date=February 22, 2014 }} Asociaci\u00f3n de Salas de Conciertos de Catalu\u00f1a. 2014. Retrieved February 13, 2014.</ref>\n\nRosa ended the tour in his native Puerto Rico, where he sold out the island's recently opened new 18,000-seat arena, [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot Coliseum|Coliseo de Puerto Rico Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot]].{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} Titled \"Draco al Natural\", the concert was the basis for a CD/DVD, offering a full-length documentary of the live performance directed by Rosa's wife, Angela Alvarado, and released in 2005. Rosa also presented sold-out concerts at [[Luis A. Ferr\u00e9 Performing Arts Center|Centro de Bellas Artes]] in September of that year. After this, his contract with Sony Records ended and he released his second album in Spanish titled ''[[Vino (album)|Vino]]'' in 2008, which Rosa considers as the follow up album to [[Vagabundo]]<ref>[http://www.sesac.com/News/News_Details.aspx?id=1716 ''Puerto Rican Singer, Songwriter, Producer and Icon Robi \u2018Draco\u2019 Rosa signs with SESAC.''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222161544/http://www.sesac.com/News/News_Details.aspx?id=1716 |date=February 22, 2014 }} SESAC. May 21, 2012. Retrieved February 13, 2014.</ref> and is included in his production ''Draco: Limited Collector's Edition'', along with the ''Teatro Live'' DVD.\n\n===''Amor Vincit Omnia'' (2009\u201311)===\nRosa yet again honored his roots in 2009 with the release of ''Amor Vincit Omnia'' (''Love Conquers All''). A collection of songs with a heavy influence of Puerto Rican folk music. Songs like \"Esto es Vida\", \"Amores de mi Calle\" and \"Espejismo\" have the old-school feel of mountain music of yesteryear. The critically acclaimed album received a [[52nd Grammy Awards|2010 Grammy]] nomination for \"Best Latin Rock Alternative Album\" and received the Rock Record of the Year at [[Premio Lo Nuestro 2011|Premios Lo Nuestro 2011]] with two other nominations for Artist and Song of the Year. A successful tour followed culminating in [[Rock in Rio]] in Madrid, where Rosa shared the main stage with [[Jane's Addiction]] and [[Rage Against the Machine]].\n\n===Stage comeback and ''Vida'' (2012\u20132014)===\n{{see also|Vida (Draco Rosa album)}}\nOn January 28, 2012, Rosa made a comeback to the public light after his long absence due to cancer treatment to announce a concert in which he will be sharing the stage with [[Juan Luis Guerra]] and [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]]. The concert took place on March 30, 2012 at the [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot Coliseum|Coliseo de Puerto Rico Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot]]. Last time the three collaborated was nearly ten years before in the [[Popular, Inc.|Banco Popular]] Christmas special ''Encuentro'' in 2002. In memory of that event, Rosa's comeback was entitled \"Encuentro\".<ref>[http://www.primerahora.com/historicojunteentredracorosarubenbladesyjuanluisguerra-607433.html ''Hist\u00f3rico junte entre Draco Rosa, Rub\u00e9n Blades y Juan Luis Guerra.''] Primera Hora.com</ref> Angelo Medina, producer of the event, announced on February 24, 2012, that the concert was quickly sold out and a second concert was added for March 31.<ref>[http://www.elnuevodia.com/abrennuevafuncionparaconciertodedracorubenbladesyjuanluisguerra-1198369.html ''Abren nueva funci\u00f3n para concierto de Draco, Rub\u00e9n Blades y Juan Luis Guerra.''] El Nuevo D\u00eda.com</ref>\n\nBoth concerts premiered two of the multiple the collaborations planned for Rosa's next album. Guerra joined Rosa in \"Esto Es Vida\" and then Blades with \"El Tiempo Va\" alongside Draco Rosa. Both shows were such big hits that rumors quickly rose about two concerts that would have taken place in Dominican Republic and Panama, home places of [[Juan Luis Guerra]] and [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]] respectively.\n\nOn October 16, 2012, Rosa's manager and friend Angelo Medina announced that the release date of Draco Rosa's new album ''[[Vida (Draco Rosa album)|Vida]]'' had been pushed back from November 13, 2012 to February 2013 due to Rosa entering quarantine after a bone marrow transplant months before. \"He's fine, he spent several months in the hospital, he was discharged and is at home in this process they call quarantine, but for 80 days, which fall due in December. Draco has been two years in this process and I am impressed by how brave he has faced the disease\", said the producer.<ref>[http://www.elnuevodia.com/encuarentenadracotrasuntrasplantedemedulaosea-1364946.html En cuarentena ''Draco tras un trasplante de m\u00e9dula \u00f3sea.''] El Nuevo D\u00eda.com</ref>\n\nAs a thank you to messages of hope and recovery, Rosa released the music video to an unpublished version of his own rendition of [[Silent Night]] in both English and Spanish on December 23, 2012, filmed at his California residence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=owNkVloDs20|title=Silent Night / Noche de Paz by Draco Rosa|date=December 23, 2012|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first official single of ''Vida'' was released on January 6, 2013. The highly anticipated duet between Draco Rosa and fellow ex-[[Menudo (band)|Menudo]] member and long-time friend [[Ricky Martin]] on \"[[M\u00e1s y M\u00e1s]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/mas-y-mas-feat.-ricky-martin/id587565290|title=iTunes Store|website=Itunes.apple.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> was released on iTunes weeks after Draco's quarantine expired and was declared cancer-free on December 31, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://musica.univision.com/estrenos-musicales/resenas/article/2013-01-15/ricky-martin-draco-juntos-cancion-mas-y-mas|title=Draco estrena dueto con Ricky titulado 'M\u00e1s y M\u00e1s'. \u00a1Esc\u00fachalo!|website=Univision.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> \"After so many years of writing and doing projects together, I felt that the right right thing was this should be the first single. Ricky is one of the main artists with whom I've worked with, so it was a great idea to do such a pretty duet. It's that kind of things that are destined to happen\", said Draco. Also, on said date, after completing his quarantine, Draco was declared cancer-free. A final statement was released on January 10, 2013, announcing that the official release date of ''Vida'' had been pushed back an additional month since Angelo Medina's October 2012 statement. The album's final release date would be March 19, 2013.\n\nAlthough both artists are not seen in person for many years, Draco said Ricky was one of the many friends who gave him support in one of the most difficult stages that he lives, who has been fighting cancer for the past two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/dracoconfirmaquenotienecancer-1424498.html|title=Portada - El Nuevo D\u00eda|work=El Nuevo Dia|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> As part of the new projects, Draco and Ricky participated together in the recording of the single's music video in New York under the direction of Carlos P\u00e9rez.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entretenimiento.prodigy.msn.com/celebridades/ricky-martin-graba-video-de-m%C3%A1s-y-m%C3%A1s-con-draco-rosa-1|title=Cartelera, M\u00fasica, Programaci\u00f3n de TV y Famosos en Prodigy MSN|website=Entretenimiento.prodigy.msn.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231004321/http://entretenimiento.prodigy.msn.com/celebridades/ricky-martin-graba-video-de-m%C3%A1s-y-m%C3%A1s-con-draco-rosa-1|archive-date=December 31, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/article/draco-rosa-y-ricky-martin-graban-juntos-el-video-de-mas-y-mas|title=Draco Rosa y Ricky Martin graban juntos el v\u00eddeo de \"M\u00e1s y m\u00e1s\"|website=PeopleenEspanol.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.super-stereo.mx/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9694%3Afilma-ricky-martin-video-con-draco&catid=82%3Acatalinstante&Itemid=69|title=Super Stereo 100.5 FM - Al ritmo de tu ciudad|website=Super-stereo.mx|accessdate=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230235550/http://www.super-stereo.mx/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9694%3Afilma-ricky-martin-video-con-draco&catid=82%3Acatalinstante&Itemid=69|archive-date=December 30, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinembargo.mx/16-01-2013/492594|title=\u00c9l es un m\u00fasico genio, y el otro, un rey del pop; Robi Draco y Ricky Martin se juntan en Nueva York|work=SinEmbargo MX|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Vida'' was recorded in Spain, England, Mexico, Argentina, United States and Puerto Rico.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mx.mujer.yahoo.com/draco-calienta-motores-lanzamiento-disco-flamante-video-ricky-055627352.html|title=Yahoo|work=Yahoo|accessdate=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130217020829/http://mx.mujer.yahoo.com/draco-calienta-motores-lanzamiento-disco-flamante-video-ricky-055627352.html|archive-date=February 17, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe 2013 edition of the [[:es:Fiestas de la Calle San Sebasti\u00e1n|San Sebastian St. Festival]], considered to be Puerto Rico's final Christmas celebration, was dedicated to Draco for his outstanding career.\n\nThe first live performance of the album took place at [[Lo Nuestro Awards|Premios Lo Nuestro 2013]] where Draco and Ricky Martin shared the stage to perform live their single \"M\u00e1s y M\u00e1s\" for the first time since they were both in [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/rickymartinydracocantaranjuntosenpremioslonuestro-1447736.html|title=Portada - El Nuevo D\u00eda|work=El Nuevo Dia|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://musica.univision.com/premio-lo-nuestro/lo-ultimo/article/2013-02-13/video-musical-mas-y-mas-draco-y-ricky-martin-estreno|title=Ricky Martin y Draco van a Premio Lo Nuestro|website=Univision.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218184720/http://musica.univision.com/premio-lo-nuestro/lo-ultimo/article/2013-02-13/video-musical-mas-y-mas-draco-y-ricky-martin-estreno|archive-date=February 18, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2013, previous to the 2013 [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]], Draco received the first Premio Conquistador given by the [[Latin Songwriters Hall of Fame]] at the [[New World Center]] in Miami and presented to him by [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]]. After the presentation of the award, Draco and Rub\u00e9n shared the stage to perform a duet of \"El Tiempo Va\", included in ''[[Vida (Draco Rosa album)|Vida]]''. Two days after, Draco and Mexican band [[Man\u00e1]] performed \"Pen\u00e9lope\" together at the 2013 [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]], held at the [[BankUnited Center]] in Miami on April 25, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/global/1556644/draco-rosa-and-mexicos-mana-performing-together-at-billboard-latin|title=Draco Rosa and Mexico's Man\u00e1 Performing Together at Billboard Latin Music Awards|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laprensafl.com/mana-draco-rosa-cantaran-juntos-premios-billboard#.UWOWM5M3uSo|title=Man\u00e1 y Draco Rosa cantar\u00e1n juntos en Premios Billboard (video)|date=April 9, 2013|website=Laprensafl.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130507074229/http://www.laprensafl.com/mana-draco-rosa-cantaran-juntos-premios-billboard#.UWOWM5M3uSo|archive-date=May 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.broadwayworld.com/article/Mana-Draco-Rosa-to-Debut-New-Single-at-Billboard-Latin-Music-Awards-425-20130408|title=Mana & Draco Rosa to Debut New Single at Billboard Latin Music Awards, 4/25|author=Music News Desk|website=Music.broadwayworld.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter making a special appearance at [[Alejandro Sanz]]'s concert in Puerto Rico on May 12, 2013, in which both sang their duet of \"Como Me Acuerdo\", Draco and Sanz's duet was filmed and used for the music video released on October 21, 2013, which was removed from YouTube the same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/dracoseraelinvitadodealejandrosanzensuconcierto-1508492.html|title=Portada - El Nuevo D\u00eda|work=El Nuevo Dia|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter making his first ever appearance at the [[Puerto Rican Day Parade]] on June 9, 2013 and performing at the [[Copacabana (nightclub)|Copacabana]] in [[Times Square]] on May 11, 2013, Draco confirmed that he will film the music video for duet of \"Esto Es Vida\" with [[Juan Luis Guerra]] in the Dominican Republic which he appraised during his illness as one of his \"best compositions\". \"It was a strong moment in my life. They're important parts with serious people, important\", he expressed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/dracoencuentrasuproposito-1528607.html|title=Draco encuentra su 'prop\u00f3sito'|website=El Nuevo Dia|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.primerahora.com/entretenimiento/musica/nota/robidracorosasegozalaparadapuertorriquena-928008/|title=Robi Draco Rosa se goza la Parada Puertorrique\u00f1a|work=Primera Hora|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> Filming took place on June 17, 2013 at the ruins of the [[Engombe Sugar Mill]] in [[Santo Domingo]]. The video was directed by Guerra's own son, Jean Gabriel Guerra, a filmmaker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.primerahora.com/entretenimiento/musica/nota/dracorosayjuanluisguerraseunenenvideomusical-930205/|title=Draco Rosa y Juan Luis Guerra se unen en video musical|work=Primera Hora|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/930333.html|title=El Universal - Espect\u8c29culos - Guerra y Draco Rosa graban video de Esto es vida|date=June 17, 2013|website=Eluniversal.com.mx|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://novamix.cienradios.com.ar/2013/06/18/robi-draco-rosa-y-juan-luis-guerra-juntos-en-esto-es-vida/|title=Robi Draco Rosa y Juan Luis Guerra, juntos en \"Esto es vida\"|website=Novamix.cienradios.com.ar|accessdate=October 27, 2018|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130707162059/http://novamix.cienradios.com.ar/2013/06/18/robi-draco-rosa-y-juan-luis-guerra-juntos-en-esto-es-vida/|archive-date=July 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The music video was released on August 14, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zEFmCx4t1-I|title=Draco Rosa - Esto Es Vida (Nueva Version) ft. Juan Luis Guerra|date=August 14, 2013|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDraco made his return to the stage on December 6, 2013 at the [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot Coliseum|Coliseo de Puerto Rico Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot]] with a concert entitled \"Draco & Friends\". Many artists who collaborated on ''Vida'' performed alongside Draco, including [[Juan Luis Guerra]], [[Enrique Bunbury]], [[Calle 13 (band)|Calle 13]]'s [[Residente|Ren\u00e9 P\u00e9rez]], [[Juanes]] and [[Ricky Martin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ticketpop.com/es/events/detail/draco-and-friends-1|title=Ticketpop :: Draco ...|website=Ticketpop.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011205229/http://www.ticketpop.com/es/events/detail/draco-and-friends-1|archive-date=October 11, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kq105.univision.com/videos/video/2013-03-26/draco-rosa-concert-en-pr|title=Draco Rosa: Concert en PR|website=Univision.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> Draco announced that due to overwhelming demand, a second concert date was added for December 7, 2013, which featured other guest artists performing alongside him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/dracoabresegundafuncionenelcoliseodepuertorico-1626498.html|title=Draco abre segunda funci\u00f3n en el Coliseo de Puerto Rico|website=El Nuevo Dia|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Book, future projects and Monte Sagrado (2015\u2013present)===\nAlong with the authorship of Nena Niessen, it was announced on May 6, 2015 that Draco would release his first publication, a cookbook on nutritional and alternative cooking divided into three sections: the first devoted to fundamental ingredients for good health, the second dealing with body detox and the third with recipes easy to prepare dishes that combine a good and important nutrition detoxification. The book, entitled ''El Secreto de la Vida a Base De Plantas'' (''The Secret of Life Based on Plants'') was released late July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/entretenimiento/musica/nota/dracodebutacomoautordelibros-2043893/|title=Draco debuta como autor de libros|date=May 6, 2015|website=Elnuevodia.com|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.pr/estilo-de-vida/draco-se-aferra-a-la-vida-a-traves-de-una-sana-alimentacion/pGXoij!w9IpQsPHCszgw/|title=Draco se aferra a la vida a trav\u00e9s de una sana alimentaci\u00f3n|website=Metro.pr|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Monte Sagrado'', Rosa's first album of original material in over a decade, was released on October 26, 2018. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' 's [[David Fricke]] called it \"one of the (most) honest records you will hear this year \u2014 at any volume, in any language.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/draco-rosa-monte-sagrado-746079/|title=Review: Draco Rosa Indulges His Dark Side in Comeback LP, \u2018Monte Sagrado\u2019|first=David|last=Fricke|date=October 26, 2018|website=Rollingstone.com|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Family===\nRosa was born '''Robert Edward Rosa Su\u00e1rez''' on [[Long Island]], New York to [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] parents, Norberto Rosa and Sonia Su\u00e1rez, and was raised in [[Pe\u00f1uelas, Puerto Rico|Pe\u00f1uelas]] and [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]]. He is fluent in Spanish, English, German and Portuguese. Draco is married to actress [[Angela Alvarado]] with whom he has two sons, Revel, born in 1994, and Redamo, born in 2001. He currently resides in [[Los Angeles]] and occasionally in [[Utuado, Puerto Rico|Utuado]].\n\n===Entrepreneurial life===\nDraco owns a recording studio, an independent music label and a multimedia company under the name of Phantom Vox. He also owns Hacienda Horizonte in the mountains of [[Utuado, Puerto Rico|Utuado]], where his recording studio is being relocated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/dracoiniciaeltrasladodesuestudioalaisla-1711798.html|title=Draco inicia el traslado de su estudio a la Isla|work=El Nuevo Dia|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> and where the music videos for \"Para\u00edso Prometido\" and \"Reza Por M\u00ed\" from the album ''Amor Vincit Omnia'' have been filmed. Aside from the many different projects in Utuado, Draco also created his own line of rum, Ron Vagabundo with the [[Destiler\u00eda Serrall\u00e9s|Serrall\u00e9s Destillery]]; a brand of locally grown coffee, Caf\u00e9 Horizonte and a clothing line, Vagabundo Clothing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vagabundoclothing.com/|title=DRACO - VAGABUNDO POR EL MUNDO CLOTHING|website=Vagabundoclothing.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218091252/http://vagabundoclothing.com/|archive-date=December 18, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Puerto Rico's Chamber of Commerce awarded Draco with the Zenit award as Businessman of the Year in 2011.\n\nOn December 10, 2013, Draco was recognized by the [[House of Representatives of Puerto Rico]] at the [[Capitol of Puerto Rico|Capitol Building of Puerto Rico]] for his successful career while in recovery from cancer at the recent light of his relapse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/dracorecibehomenajeenelcapitolio-1663671.html|title=Positivo Draco ante su lucha contra el c\u00e1ncer|website=El Nuevo Dia|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropic work===\nOutside of his personal investments, musical and otherwise, he has also contributed towards the improvement of artistic and cultural life in Puerto Rico, sponsoring the [[Puerto Rico Museum of Contemporary Art|Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Puerto Rico]] and setting up an annual scholarship for outstanding students at the [[Conservatory of Music of Puerto Rico]].\n\n===Arrest in Vieques===\nOn April 9, 2001, Rosa, who was vehemently opposed to the U.S. Government's use of [[Vieques]] as a military training site, and had been a very vocal supporter of the [[environmental movement]] and the [[Independence movement in Puerto Rico|independence movement]], was arrested alongside Senator [[Luis Guti\u00e9rrez]], [[Edward James Olmos]], [[Robert Kennedy Jr.]] and other protesters for civil disobedience when they invaded the U.S. Navy's security zone surrounding the Island of Vieques.\n\n===Drug abuse===\nShortly after leaving Menudo, Rosa started taking drugs, and often drew inspiration from hallucinogens and alcohol for his songwriting. Although this generated heavy criticism, most of his fans did not seem to be bothered by this. Rosa has always been very open about the subject, even admitting that his wife, Angela, saved his life on at least one occasion. Rosa stopped taking drugs in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inyenagilgalad.blogspot.com/2007/08/entrevista-draco.html|title=los despistes de ereinion|author=Gil-Galad|website=Inyenagolgalad.blogspot.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Illness===\nOn April 25, 2011, Rosa was diagnosed with cancer: a [[non-Hodgkin lymphoma]], near his liver.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.ocweekly.com/heardmentality/2011/04/robi_draco_rosa_diagnosed_with.php|title=Robi Draco Rosa Diagnosed With Cancer|author=Roxy Law|date=April 25, 2011|work=Heard Mentality|accessdate=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011043254/http://blogs.ocweekly.com/heardmentality/2011/04/robi_draco_rosa_diagnosed_with.php|archive-date=October 11, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> He followed several alternative treatments, such as high [[vitamin C]] doses or neoplasm treatment at the [[Burzynski Clinic]] in [[Houston]]. Finally, he underwent conventional treatments of chemotherapy and bone marrow transplantation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/02/robi-draco-rosa-cancer-free_n_3368736.html|title=Robi Draco Rosa Confirms He Is Officially Cancer Free Via Twitter|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> He was under quarantine in his California home until December 31, 2012, when Draco completed his quarantine and was declared cancer-free. On May 30, 2013, Rosa tweeted that his recent cancer study resulted negative, confirming he is completely cured of cancer. His tweet read: \"Familia: I went in yesterday for a pet scan. Today my results came in; I'm free. So happy!! #cancerfree #celebration#love #faith #gratitude\" (''sic'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.primerahora.com/entretenimiento/farandula/nota/dracoconfirmaqueestaliberadodelcancer-925401/|title=Draco confirma que est\u00e1 liberado del cancer|work=Primera Hora|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn December 9, 2013, Rosa's manager confirmed that Draco's cancer had relapsed in a press conference for the [[World's Best 10K]] on February 23, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latintimes.com/articles/10979/20131209/robbie-draco-rosa-cancer-update-musician-relapses.htm#.UqZ0K-IZO00|title=Robbie Draco Rosa Cancer Update: The Musician Relapses In Silence; Doctors Think He Can Win The Battle Again|date=December 10, 2013|work=Latin Times|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> A routine test taken while on tour, led to the diagnosis of a [[Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma|diffuse B-cell lymphoma]], non-Hodgkin type, which his doctors consider he may recover from again. Draco himself told his manager the night of the [[Latin Grammy Awards of 2013|2013 Latin Grammys]]. Rosa was declared again cancer-free on January 5, 2014.<ref name=VocesHuff/> Rosa initially had planned to participate at the 10K on behalf of a 9-year-old patient, who was recovering from a bone marrow transplant but his own recovery and quarantine prevented Rosa from participating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/dracoseenfrentadenuevoalcancer-1662936.html|title=Portada - El Nuevo D\u00eda|work=El Nuevo Dia|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> Rosa, instead, sent his wife Angela and son Redamo in his place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/familiadedracoconoceaninosobrevivientedecancer-1717575.html|title=Familia de Draco conoce a ni\u00f1o sobreviviente de c\u00e1ncer|work=El Nuevo Dia|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> On February 26, Draco commenced his second bone marrow transplant in California and remained in quarantine for a course of four months before being declared cancer-free once again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/dracorosasesometehoyatrasplantedemedulaosea-1720312.html|title=Draco Rosa se somete hoy a trasplante de m\u00e9dula \u00f3sea|work=El Nuevo Dia|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 23, 2018, Rosa announced by way of a video post on Instagram that after his last check-up examinations he is completely cancer-free, information that was corroborated by his manager Wanda Troche.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/espana/gente/draco-rosa-anuncia-que-esta-libre-del-cancer-sufrio-durante-anos/10007-3728157|title=Draco Rosa anuncia que est\u00e1 libre del c\u00e1ncer que sufri\u00f3 durante a\u00f1os|website=www.efe.com|language=es|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aarp.org/espanol/salud/enfermedades-y-tratamientos/info-2019/draco-rosa-dice-estar-libre-de-cancer.html|title=Draco Rosa dice estar libre de c\u00e1ncer|last=Catron|first=Jennifer Garc\u00eda|website=AARP|language=spanish|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> Rosa celebrated his fifth cancer-free anniversary in another Instagram post from February 28, 2019.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BucexP4lFz3/|title=Draco Rosa on Instagram: \u201cI can\u2019t stop thinking about a huge milestone that has kept me up the last few nights. 5 years Cancer free since February 26th 2014 -\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n'''With Menudo'''\n* ''[[Reaching Out]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Mania (Menudo album)|Man\u00eda]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Evoluci\u00f3n (Menudo album)|Evoluci\u00f3n]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Menudo (album)|Menudo]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Explosion]]'' Japanese Album (1985)\n* ''[[Ayer y Hoy (Menudo album)|Ayer y Hoy]]'' (1985)\n* ''A Festa Vai Comecar (1985)\n* ''[[Viva! Bravo!]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Refrescante]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Can't Get Enough (Menudo album)|Can't Get Enough]]'' (1986)\n\n'''With Maggie's Dream'''\n* ''[[Maggie's Dream (1990 album)|Maggie's Dream]]'' (1990)\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Solo'''\n* ''Robby'' (1988) [as '''Robby''']<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/Robby-Robby/release/7520497 Robby - ''Robby'' @Discogs.com] Retrieved 11-19-2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qGdEtgVsDRs Robby Rosa- \"Como de Costume\" music video @YouTube.com (includes images of Robby's 1989 solo album)] Retrieved April 26, 2013.</ref>\n* ''Robby'' (a.k.a. ''Ser Feliz'') (1989) [as '''Robby''']<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/Robby-Ser-Feliz/release/5791002 Robby - ''Ser Feliz'' @Discogs.com] Retrieved 11-19-2016.</ref>\n* ''[[Frio (album)|Fr\u00edo]]'' (1994)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/frio/id191226557|title=iTunes - Music - Frio by Robi Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''[[Vagabundo]]'' (1996)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/vagabundo/id190320609|title=iTunes - Music - Vagabundo by Robi Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''Songbirds & Roosters'' (1998)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/songbirds-roosters/id203793303|title=iTunes - Music - Songbirds & Roosters by Robi Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''Libertad del Alma'' (2001)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/libertad-del-alma/id203939575|title=iTunes - Music - Libertad del Alma by Robi Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''[[Mad Love (Robi Draco Rosa album)|Mad Love]]'' (2004)\n* ''Como Me Acuerdo'' (2004)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/como-me-acuerdo/id157901827|title=iTunes - Music - Como Me Acuerdo by Robi Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''Draco y El Teatro del Absurdo'' (2007)\n* ''[[Vino (album)|Vino]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/vino/id288833254|title=iTunes - Music - Vino by Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''Amor Vincit Omnia'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/amor-vincit-omnia/id555113352|title=iTunes - Music - Amor V\u00edncit Omnia by Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''[[Vida (Draco Rosa album)|Vida]]'' (2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/vida/id617079859|title=iTunes - Music - Vida by Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''Monte Sagrado'' (2018)\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Live albums'''\n* ''Draco Al Natural'' (2005)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/draco-al-natural/id309078966|title=iTunes - Music - Draco Al Natural by Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''[[Teatro (Draco Rosa album)|Teatro Live]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/teatro-live/id292126370|title=iTunes - Music - Teatro Live by Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''731 Ensayos Al Natural'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/ensayos-al-natural/id304275354|title=iTunes - Music - Ensayos al Natural by Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Extended Plays'''\n* ''La Pena Negra'' (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/la-pena-negra/id417475555|title=iTunes - Music - La Pena Negra by Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''Forest of Numbers (Rock It!)'' (2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/forest-numbers-rock-it!-feat./id537770489|title=iTunes - Music - Forest of Numbers (Rock It!) [feat. Mr. Blake] - EP by Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Experimental works'''\n* ''Heronepheus \"King of the Void\"'' (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/heronepheus-king-void-single/id427616521|title=iTunes - Music - Heronepheus \"King of the Void\" - Single by Draco Rosa|work=iTunes|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Soundtracks'''\n* ''[[Salsa (1988 film)#Soundtrack|Salsa: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]'' (1988)\n* ''Encuentro'' (2002)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Encuentro-Robi-Draco-Rosa/dp/B00026VVE6|title=Amazon.com: Robi Draco Rosa, Juan Luis Guerra, Ruben Blades: Encuentro: Music|website=Amazon.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Tours==\n* M\u00e1s All\u00e1 del Rock\n* Re-Vive el Teatro\n* Draco Rosa: Libre, Natural, Puro\n* Mad Love Tour\n* Draco y su Para\u00edso\n* Vagabundo Por El Mundo World Tour\n* Amor Vincit Omnia\n* Vida World Tour\n* Lo Sagrado y Lo Maldito Tour\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Salsa (1988 film)|Salsa]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Gummib\u00e4rchen k\u00fc\u00dft man nicht]]'' (1989)\n* ''Homens de Verdade N\u00e3o Mascam Chiclete'' (1990)\n* ''Livin' the Life'' (1999) <small>(Music Director)</small>\n* ''Encuentro'' (2002) <small>(alongside [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]] and [[Juan Luis Guerra]])</small>\n* ''Draco Al Natural'' (2005)\n* ''Draco: Limited Collector's Edition'' (2007)\n* ''Teatro Live'' (2008)\n\n==Composer and Producer==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:140px;\"| Artist\n! style=\"width:175px;\"| Album\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1998\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[Ricky Martin]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|''[[Vuelve (album)|Vuelve]]''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|1999\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|''[[Ricky Martin (1999 album)|Ricky Martin]]''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Ednita Nazario]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|''[[Coraz\u00f3n (Ednita Nazario album)|Coraz\u00f3n]]''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|2000\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Ricky Martin]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|''[[Sound Loaded]]''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Julio Iglesias]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|''[[Noche De Cuatro Lunas (Julio Iglesias album)|Noche De Cuatro Lunas]]''\n|}\n\n==Books==\n{{cite book |first1=Draco |last1=Rosa |first2=Nena |last2=Niessen |date=2015 |title=El Secreto de la Vida a Base De Plantas |trans-title=The Secret of Plant-Based Life |url=https://www.amazon.com/secreto-vida-plantas-Spanish-Edition/dp/1941999468 |language=Spanish |location=Puerto Rico |publisher=Penguin Random House |isbn=}}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n;Grammy Awards\nThe [[Grammy Award]] is an accolade by the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]] of the United States to recognize outstanding achievement on the music industry.\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[42nd Grammy Awards|2000]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\"[[Livin' la Vida Loca]]\"\n|[[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] <small>(as producer)</small>\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] <small>(as songwriter)</small>\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[53rd Annual Grammy Awards|2011]]\n|''Amor Vincit Omnia''\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Rock, Urban or Alternative Album|Best Latin Rock, Urban or Alternative Album]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[56th Annual Grammy Awards|2014]]\n|''[[Vida (Draco Rosa album)|Vida]]''\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]]\n|{{Won}}<ref name=Grammy2014>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/22/grammy-winners-list_n_4646243.html|title=Grammy Winners List 2014: Daft Punk, Macklemore, Lorde & More|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n{{end}}\n\n;Latin Grammy Awards\nA [[Latin Grammy Award]] is an accolade by the [[Latin Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences]] to recognize outstanding achievement in the Latin music industry.\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|[[Latin Grammy Awards of 2004|2004]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|\"[[M\u00e1s y M\u00e1s]]\"\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video|Best Music Video]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[Latin Grammy Awards of 2009|2009]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Teatro (Draco Rosa album)|Teatro]]''\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Rock Solo Vocal Album|Best Rock Solo Vocal Album]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video|Best Long Form Music Video]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|[[Latin Grammy Awards of 2013|2013]]\n|\"[[M\u00e1s y M\u00e1s]]\" (feat. [[Ricky Martin]])\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Vida (Draco Rosa album)|Vida]]''\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Pop Vocal Album|Best Contemporary Pop Vocal Album]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[Latin Grammy Awards of 2019|2019]]\n|''Monte Sagrado''\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Rock Album|Best Rock Album]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|\"Hotel De Los Encuentros\"\n|[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video|Best Long Form Music Video]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n;Lo Nuestro Awards\n[[Lo Nuestro Awards]] ({{lang-es|link=no|Premios Lo Nuestro}}) is an awards show honoring the best of [[Latin music (genre)|Latin music]], presented by television network [[Univision]].\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|[[Premio Lo Nuestro 2011|2011]]\n|''Amor Vincit Omnia''\n|Album of the Year: Rock\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Himself\n|Artist of the Year: Rock\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|\"Esto Es Vida\"\n|Song of the Year: Rock\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Biography|Latin music}}\n*[[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=note/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://dracorosa.com Draco Rosa]\n\n{{Draco Rosa|state=collapsed}}{{Menudo|state=autocollapse}}\n{{Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosa, Draco}}\n[[Category:Draco Rosa]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Puerto Rican male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American child singers]]\n[[Category:American multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin music songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Menudo (band) members]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Ponce]]\n[[Category:People from Long Island]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican independence activists]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican rock singers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Rock en Espa\u00f1ol musicians]]\n[[Category:Sony Music Latin artists]]\n[[Category:Singers from Ponce]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "24.48.215.37", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Took out unsourced material)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Draco_Rosa"}
